 New Data to Help Ensure Urban Growth Benefits the Poor], The World Bank Group, 26 Jan 2015</ref> where [[Hong Kong]] and [[Shenzhen]] are located). This was completed in November 2018.<ref name=electrekswap/>\n\nThe second phase consisted of installing battery-swap stations in 8 locations along the [[G2 Beijing\u2013Shanghai Expressway|G2 expressway]], a {{convert|1212|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} road connecting Beijing with [[Shanghai]]. This phase was completed in January 2019.<ref>https://twitter.com/NIOGlobal/status/1085431718679592960</ref>\n\n==Sales==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Calendar year\n!EP9\n!ES6<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carsalesbase.com/china-car-sales-data/nio/nio-es6/|title=NIO ES6 China Auto Sales Figures|publisher=CarSalesBase.com|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n!ES8<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carsalesbase.com/china-car-sales-data/nio/nio-es8/|title=NIO ES8 China Auto Sales Figures|publisher=CarSalesBase.com|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n!Total\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|6\n|0\n|0\n|6\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|10*\n|0\n|8,101\n|8,111*\n|*Number not confirmed\n|-\n|2019\n|0\n|20,204\n|8,872\n|29,076\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|0*\n|1,493*\n|105*\n|1,598*\n|Sales drop in early 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]<br/>*As of January 2020\n|-\n|Total\n|16*\n|21,697*\n|17,078*\n|38,791*\n|*As of January 2020\n|}\n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== NOMI AI===\n\nNOMI, an artificial-intelligence technology, claimed to be the first in-car AI system in production vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autodevot.com/2018/07/nio-starts-delivering-es8-electric-suvs-nomi-ai/|title=NIO starts delivering ES8 electric SUVs with NOMI AI|publisher=Autodevot|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> NOMI can pull up the cars navigation, control the music, and unique to NIO cars can take a selfie of the passengers in the cabin.\n\n== Motorsport ==\n===Formula E===\n{{main|NIO Formula E Team}}\n[[File:Nio Formula E car.jpg|thumb|220x220px|NIO have been participating in the [[Formula E|ABB FIA Formula E]] since 2014, the inaugural season.]]\n\nNIO first joined the [[Formula E]] championship series in its inaugural [[2014\u201315 Formula E season|2014\u20132015 season]] with their counterpart formerly known as [[NIO Formula E Team|China Racing Formula E Team]]. For the season, the team had [[Ho-Pin Tung]] and [[Charles Pic]] drive the #88 car, and Brazilian driver [[Nelson Piquet Jr.]] drive the #99 car. They team went on to win the inaugural FIA Formula E Drivers' Championship in July 2015 with [[Nelson Piquet Jr.]], and also winning two races, the [[2015 Long Beach ePrix]] and the [[2015 Moscow ePrix]].\n\nThe second season in the Formula E, allowed teams to be able to develop new powertrains for the season. The team used its own NextEV chassis and powertrains for the season.\n\nFrom the inaugural season of the series to present, NextEV has not won a Constructors' Championship yet and has yet to win one, but has won a Drivers' Championship, and two races, the [[2015 Long Beach ePrix]] and the [[2015 Moscow ePrix]], both races from the [[2014\u201315 Formula E season|2014\u20132015 Formula E season]]. NIO secured the inaugural FIA Formula E Drivers's Championship in July 2015.\n\n== World records ==\n\nNIO set five records in their track-only EP9 for the fastest lap for an electric-powered car in the [[N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife]], [[Circuit Paul Ricard]], [[Circuit of the Americas]], and [[Shanghai International Circuit]] tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/electric/video-watch-nio-ep9s-645-ring-record|title=Video: watch the Nio EP9\u2019s 6:45 \u2018Ring record|website=www.topgear.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Aion (car brand)|Aion]]\n* [[BYD Auto|BYD]]\n* [[Byton (company)|Byton]]\n* [[Faraday Future]]\n* [[Fisker Inc.]]\n* [https://www.human-horizons.com/ Human Horizons]\n* [[Lucid Motors]]\n* [[Lynk & Co]]\n* [[Polestar]]\n* [[Rivian]]\n* [[Tesla, Inc.]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.nio.io}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = NIO Inc.\n| symbol = NIO\n| reuters = NIO.N\n| bloomberg = NIO:US\n| sec_cik = NIO\n| yahoo = NIO\n| google = NIO\n}}\n\n{{Nio (car company)}}\n{{NIO automobile timeline}}\n{{Automotive industry in China}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Electric vehicle manufacturers of China]]\n[[Category:Car brands]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of China]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in China]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Chinese companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:2018 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:NIO (car company)]]\n[[Category:Chinese brands]]\n[[Category:Luxury motor vehicle manufacturers]]\n", "name_user": "Ivan Gabriele", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add founded month", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIO_(car_company)"}
{"title_page": "Law of attraction (New Thought)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Law of attraction (disambiguation){{!}}Law of attraction}}\n{{New Thought beliefs}}\n{{Paranormal}}\nIn the [[New Thought]] philosophy, the '''[https://medium.com/@manifestingabundance/how-to-use-the-law-of-attraction-6556bf0a3a65?source=friends_link&sk=8c87aa0151d33fb50221bd49c3ec3aa6 Law of Attraction]''' is the belief that positive or negative thoughts bring positive or negative experiences into a person's life.<ref name=gazette>Whittaker, S. [http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/story.html?id=78fc94dd-c0b2-4ade-891d-98770bfae388&k=70777 Secret attraction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090328/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/story.html?id=78fc94dd-c0b2-4ade-891d-98770bfae388&k=70777 |date=2016-03-04 }}, ''The Montreal Gazette'', May 12, 2007.</ref><ref>Redden, Guy, \"Magic Happens: A New Age Metaphysical Mystery Tour\", ''Journal of Australian Studies'': 101</ref> The belief is based on the ideas that people and their thoughts are made from \"pure energy\", and that a process of like energy attracting like energy exists through which a person can improve their health, wealth, and personal relationships. There is zero empirical scientific evidence supporting the law of attraction, and it is widely considered a pseudoscience. \n\nAdvocates generally combine [[cognitive reframing]] techniques with affirmations and [[creative visualization]] to replace limiting or self-destructive (\"negative\") thoughts with more empowered, adaptive (\"positive\") thoughts. A key component of the philosophy is the idea that in order to effectively change one's negative thinking patterns, one must also \"feel\" (through [[creative visualization]]) that the desired changes have already occurred. This combination of positive thought and positive emotion is believed to allow one to attract positive experiences and opportunities by achieving resonance with the proposed energetic law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelawofattraction.com/what-is-the-law-of-attraction/|title=What Is The Law Of Attraction|last1=Hurst|first1=Katherine|date=|website=The Law Of Attraction|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe Law of Attraction has no scientific basis<ref name=\"Scientific American\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Shermer | first = Michael\n  | authorlink = Michael Shermer\n  | title = The (Other) Secret\n  | journal = [[Scientific American]]\n  | volume = 296\n  | issue = 6\n  | pages = 39\n  | date = 1 June 2007\n  | doi = 10.1038/scientificamerican0607-39\n  | pmid = 17663221\n }}</ref> and has been dubbed a [[pseudoscience]].<ref name=\"Live Science\">{{cite web\n  | last = Radford | first = Benjamin\n  | authorlink = Benjamin Radford\n  | title = The Pseudoscience of 'The Secret'\n  | work = [[Live Science]]\n  | date = 3 February 2009\n  | url = http://www.livescience.com/5303-pseudoscience-secret.html\n  | accessdate = 31 March 2017\n}}</ref> A number of researchers have criticized the misuse of scientific concepts by its proponents.<ref name=\"Scientific American\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Stenger |first=Victor J. |title=Cosmic Mind |url=http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |publisher=University of Colorado |authorlink=Victor_Stenger |pages=8\u201319 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013317/http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"Leon Lederman 1993 189\u2013198\">{{cite book |title=The God Particle: If the Universe is the Answer, What is the Question |pages=189\u2013198 |author=Leon Lederman |author2=Dick Teresi |date=1993 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company}}</ref><ref name=\"plato.stanford.edu\">[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/pseudo-science/#NonSciPosSci Non-science posing as science; Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[New Thought]] movement grew out of the teachings of [[Phineas Quimby]] in the early 19th century. Early in his life, Quimby was diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]]. Early 19th century medicine had no reliable cure for tuberculosis. Quimby took to horse riding and noted that intense excitement temporarily relieved him from his affliction. This method for relieving his pain and seemingly subsequent recovery prompted Phineas to pursue a study of \"Mind over Body\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hughes|first1=n|title=Phineas Parkhurst Quimby|url=http://phineasquimby.wwwhubs.com/|accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref>  Although he never used the words \"Law of Attraction\", he explained this in a statement that captured the concept in the field of health: {{quote|the trouble is in the mind, for the body is only the house for the mind to dwell in, and we put a value on it according to its worth. Therefore if your mind has been deceived by some invisible enemy into a belief, you have put it into the form of a disease, with or without your knowledge. By my theory or truth, I come in contact with your enemy and restore you to your health and happiness. This I do partly mentally and partly by talking till I correct the wrong impressions and establish the Truth, and the Truth is the cure.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Quimby Manuscripts|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/quimbyPhineas/manuscripts/pages/quimby-manuscripts-194.htm|publisher=New Thought library|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\nIn 1877, the term \"Law of Attraction\" appeared in print for the first time in a book written by the Russian occultist [[Helena Blavatsky]], in a context alluding to an attractive power existing between elements of spirit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isis Unveiled|url=http://www.theosociety.org/pasadena/isis/iu1-10.htm|publisher=Theosophical University Press, page 340|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first articulator of the Law as general principle was [[Prentice Mulford]]. Mulford, a pivotal figure in the development of New Thought thinking, discusses the Law of Attraction at length in his essay \"The Law of Success\",<ref>{{cite book|title=Your Forces and How to Use Them, Vol. 1|url=https://archive.org/stream/yourforcesandho09mulfgoog#page/n66/mode/2up|publisher=New York, F.J. Needham|year=1888}}</ref> published 1886-1887. In this, Mulford was followed by other New Thought authors, such as Henry Wood (starting with his ''God\u2019s Image in Man'',<ref>{{cite book|title=God's Image in Man, Ch. 6, \"The Universality of Law\"|url=https://archive.org/stream/godsimageinmans01woodgoog#page/n134/mode/2up|publisher=Lee and Shepard Publishers, 1892}}</ref> 1892), and [[Ralph Waldo Trine]] (starting with his first book, ''What All the World's A-Seeking'',<ref>{{cite book|title=What All the World's A-Seeking|url=https://archive.org/details/whatallworldsas00tringoog|publisher=New Canaan, Conn., Keats Pub|year=1973}}</ref> 1896). For these authors, the Law of Attraction is concerned not only about health but every aspect of life.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Tune With The Infinite|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/trineRalphWaldo/inTune/pages/in-tune-with-the-infinite-026.htm#TopOfText|publisher=New Thought Library|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE GOD IN YOU|url=http://prenticemulford.wwwhubs.com/tgiy.htm|publisher=Cornerstone Publishing, 2001|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 20th century saw a surge in interest in the subject with many books being written about it, amongst which are two of the [[List of best-selling books|best-selling books]] of all time; ''[[Think and Grow Rich]]'' (1937) by [[Napoleon Hill]], ''[[The Power of Positive Thinking]]'' (1952) by [[Norman Vincent Peale]], and ''[[You Can Heal Your Life]]'' (1984) by [[Louise Hay]]. The [[Esther Hicks|Abraham-Hicks]] material is based primarily around the Law of Attraction.\n\nIn 2006, the concept of the Law of Attraction gained renewed exposure with the release of the film ''[[The Secret (2006 film)|The Secret]]'' (2006) which was then developed into a book of the same title in 2007. The movie and book gained widespread media coverage.<ref name=gazette /><ref name=oprah1>{{cite web |url= http://www.oprah.com/spirit/The-Law-of-Attraction-Real-Life-Stories_1 |title=The Law of Attraction: Real-Life Stories - Oprah.com |work=oprah.com |accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref><ref name=oprah2>{{cite web |url= http://www.oprah.com/spirit/Go-Beyond-The-Secret_1 |title=Go Beyond 'The Secret' - Oprah.com |work=oprah.com |accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref> This was followed by a sequel, ''[[The Power (self-help book)|The Power]]'' in 2010 that talks about the law of attraction being the law of love.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Business/power-author-rhonda-byrnes-book/story?id=11421349|title=The Secret Is Out: Megahit Writer Says Power of Love Will Fill Your Bank Account|last=NANCE-NASH|first=SHERYL|date=August 18, 2010|work=ABC News|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Descriptions==\nProponents believe that the Law of Attraction is always in operation and that it brings to each person the conditions and experiences that they predominantly think about, or which they desire or expect.\n\n[[Charles F. Haanel|Charles Haanel]] wrote in ''[[The Master Key System]]'' (1912):\n{{quote|The law of attraction will certainly and unerringly bring to you the conditions, environment, and experiences in life, corresponding with your habitual, characteristic, predominant mental attitude.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Master Key System. Chapter 8, part 18.|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/haanel-charles/Master-Key-System/audioEbook/master-key-systemRAW.pdf|publisher=New Thought Library|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\n[[Ralph Waldo Trine|Ralph Trine]] wrote in ''In Tune With The Infinite'' (1897):\n{{quote|The law of attraction works universally on every plane of action, and we attract whatever we desire or expect. If we desire one thing and expect another, we become like houses divided against themselves, which are quickly brought to desolation. Determine resolutely to expect only what you desire, then you will attract only what you wish for.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Tune With The Infinite, by Ralph Trine|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/trineRalphWaldo/inTune/pages/in-tune-with-the-infinite-035.htm#TopOfText|publisher=New Thought Library|accessdate=18 June 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nIn her 2006 film ''[[The Secret (2006 film)|The Secret]]'', Rhonda Byrne emphasized thinking about what each person wants to obtain, but also to infuse the thought with the maximum possible amount of emotion. She claims the combination of thought and feeling is what attracts the desire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tameyourmind.org/articles/how-can-it-possibly-be-law-attraction-works|title=How can it possibly be that the law of attraction works?|last=Henry|first=Juliette|date=|website=www.tameyourmind.org|publisher=Transformation guide|access-date=3 Dec 2016}}</ref> Another similar book is [[James Redfield]]'s ''[[The Celestine Prophecy]]'', which says reality can be manifested by man.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Redfield|first1=James|title=The Celestine Prophecy: An Adventure|date=1993|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York}}</ref> ''The Power of Your Subconscious Mind'' by Joseph Murphy, says readers can achieve seemingly impossible goals by learning how to bring the mind itself under control. ''The Power'' by Rhonda Byrne, ''The Alchemist'' by [[Paulo Coelho]], and ''The Power of Now'' by [[Eckhart Tolle]] are similar. While personal testimonies claim the secret and the law to have worked for them, a number of skeptics have criticized Byrne's film and book. ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' called the secret pseudoscience and an \"illusion of knowledge\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chabris|first1=Christopher F.|last2=Simons|first2=Daniel J.|title=The Pseudoscience of \u2018The Secret\u2019 and \u2018The Power\u2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/26/books/review/Chabris-t.html|accessdate=2017-08-13|work=The New York Times|date=24 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Philosophical and religious basis==\nThe New Thought concept of the Law of Attraction is rooted in ideas that come from various philosophical and religious traditions.  In particular, it has been inspired by [[Hermeticism]], [[New England transcendentalism]], specific verses from the [[Bible]], and [[Hinduism]]. \n<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melanson|first1=Terry|title=Oprah Winfrey, New Thought, \"The Secret\" and the \"New Alchemy\" |url=http://www.conspiracyarchive.com/2014/07/20/oprah-winfrey-new-thought-the-secret-and-the-new-alchemy/|publisher=Conspiracy Archive|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Aoust|first1=Maja|title=The Secret Source|date=2012|publisher=Process|isbn=978-1-934170-32-8|page=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Zink|first1=Robert|title=Magical Energy Healing: The Ruach Healing Method|date=2014|publisher=Law of Attraction Solutions, Llc|isbn=978-0990825036|page=299|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6kJ8BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA299&lpg=PA299&dq=%22law+of+attraction%22+%22emerald+tablet%22#v=onepage&q=%22law%20of%20attraction%22%20%22emerald%20tablet%22&f=false|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Donker|first1=Gerald|title=Exposing the Secret Law of Attraction|date=2008|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1409236146|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sCsqAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27&dq=%22the+new+thought%22+%22law+of+attraction%22+bible#v=onepage&q=%22the%20new%20thought%22%20%22law%20of%20attraction%22%20bible&f=false|accessdate=6 November 2015}}{{self-published source|date={{subst:CURRENTMONTH}}{{subst:CURRENTYEAR}}}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harrold|first1=Glenn|title=The Answer: Supercharge the Law of Attraction and Find the Secret of True Happiness|date=2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-1409112716|url=https://books.google.com/?id=N917eoI9LzcC&pg=PT50&lpg=PT50&dq=%22law+of+attraction%22+hinduism+%22new+thought%22#v=onepage&q=%22law%20of%20attraction%22%20hinduism%20%22new%20thought%22&f=false|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=James|first1=William|title=The Varieties of Religious Experience|date=1902|publisher=Longmans Green & Co|isbn=978-1439297278|page=94|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UPLBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=william+James+%22mind-cure+is+the%22#v=onepage&q=william%20James%20%22mind-cure%20is%20the%22&f=false|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHermeticism influenced the development of European thought in the [[Renaissance]]. Its ideas were transmitted partly through [[alchemy]]. In the 18th century, [[Franz Mesmer]] studied the works of alchemists such as [[Paracelsus]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Aoust|first1=Maja|title=The Secret Source|date=2012|publisher=Process|isbn=978-1-934170-32-8|page=16}}</ref> and [[Jan Baptist van Helmont|van Helmont]].<ref name=Hist/> Van Helmont was a 17th-century [[Flemish people|Flemish]] physician who proclaimed the curative powers of the imagination.<ref name=Hist/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hedesan|first1=Georgiana D.|title=Paracelsian Medicine and Theory of Generation in 'Exterior homo', a Manuscript Probably Authored by Jan Baptist Van Helmont (1579\u20131644), ref 52|journal=Medical History|date=July 2014|volume=58|issue=3|pmc=4103403|pmid=25045180|doi=10.1017/mdh.2014.29|pages=375\u201396}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hedesan|first1=Delia Georgiana|title='Christian Philosophy': Medical Alchemy and Christian Thought in the Work of Jan Baptista Van Helmont (1579-1644)|date=2012|page= 31|url=https://ore.exeter.ac.uk/repository/bitstream/handle/10036/4083/HedesanD.pdf?sequence=4|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> This lead Mesmer to develop his ideas about [[Animal magnetism]] which [[Phineas Quimby]], the founder of New Thought, studied.<ref name=Hist>{{cite web|last1=Braden|first1=Charles S.|title=A BRIEF HISTORY OF THE NEW THOUGHT MOVEMENT.(1963)|url=http://www.surrenderworks.com/library/downloads/braden.pdf|publisher=surrenderworks.com|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=PHINEAS PARKHURST QUIMBY 1802 - 1866 Father of New Thought|url=http://phineasquimby.wwwhubs.com/|publisher=phineasquimby|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Transcendentalist movement developed in the United States immediately before the emergence of New Thought and is thought to have had a great influence on it. [[George Ripley (transcendentalist)|George Ripley]], an important figure in that movement, stated that its leading idea was \"the supremacy of mind over matter\".<ref name=Hist/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mikics|first1=David|title=The Annotated Emerson|date=2012|publisher=Belknap Press|isbn=978-0674049239|page=6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nI3uBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA6&lpg=PA6&dq=%22george+ripley%22+%22the+supremacy+of+mind+over+matter%22#v=onepage&q=%22george%20ripley%22%20%22the%20supremacy%20of%20mind%20over%20matter%22&f=false|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNew Thought authors often quote certain verses from the Bible in the context of the Law of Attraction. An example is [[Mark 11]]:24: \"Therefore I tell you, whatever you ask in prayer, believe that you have received it, and it will be yours.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark 11:24|url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=mark+11%3A24&version=RSV|publisher=Bible Gateway|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Master Key System, by Charles Haanel (1912). Chapter 11, section 17|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/haanel-charles/Master-Key-System/audioEbook/master-key-systemRAW.pdf|publisher=The New Thought Library|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=secr>{{cite book|last1=Byrne|first1=Rhonda|title=The Secret|date=2006|publisher=Beyond Words|isbn=978-1-58270-170-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/secretbyrn00byrn/page/54 54]|url=https://archive.org/details/secretbyrn00byrn/page/54}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century [[Swami Vivekananda]] traveled to the United States and gave lectures on [[Hinduism]]. These talks greatly influenced the New Thought movement and in particular, [[William Walker Atkinson]] who was one of New Thought's pioneers.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Aoust|first1=Maja|title=The Secret Source|date=2012|publisher=Process|isbn=978-1-934170-32-8|page=61}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Woodroffe|first1=John|title=Shakti and Sh\u00e2kta, Chapter 24, 12th paragraph|date=1918|publisher=Luzac & Co|isbn=978-1595479204|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/tantra/sas/sas24.htm|\naccessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'' magazine criticized the lack of [[falsifiability]] and [[testability]] of these claims.<ref name=\"csicop.org\">{{cite web|author1=Mary Carmichael |author2=Ben Radford |url=http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/secrets_and_lies/ |title=CSI &#124; Secrets and Lies |publisher=Csicop.org |date= |accessdate=2012-05-16}}</ref> Critics have asserted that the evidence provided is usually [[anecdotal]] and that, because of the [[publication bias|self-selecting nature of the positive reports]], as well as the [[Subjectivity|subjective]] nature of any results, these reports are susceptible to [[confirmation bias]] and [[selection bias]].<ref name=\"Kaptchuck\">{{cite journal |author=Kaptchuk, T., & Eisenberg, D. |year=1998 |title=The Persuasive Appeal of Alternative Medicine |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=129 |issue=12 |pmid=9867762 |pages=1061\u20135 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-129-12-199812150-00011|last2=Eisenberg |citeseerx=10.1.1.694.4798 }}</ref> Physicist [[Ali Alousi]], for instance, criticized it as unmeasurable and questioned the likelihood that thoughts can affect anything outside the head.<ref name=gazette/>\n\nThe Law of Attraction has been popularized in the early 21st century by books and films such as ''[[The Secret (book)|The Secret]]''. This 2006 film and the subsequent book<ref>{{cite book |title=The Secret |year=2006 |first=Rhonda |last=Byrne |publisher=Beyond Words Publishing |isbn=978-1-58270-170-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/secretbyrn00byrn }}</ref> use interviews with New Thought authors and speakers to explain the principles of the proposed metaphysical law that one can attract anything that one thinks about consistently. Writing for the Committee for Skeptical Inquiry, [[Mary Carmichael]] and [[Ben Radford]] wrote that \"neither the film nor the book has any basis in scientific reality\", and that its premise contains \"an ugly flipside: if you have an accident or disease, it's your fault\".<ref name=\"csicop.org\"/>\n\nOthers have questioned the references to modern scientific theory, and have maintained, for example, that the Law of Attraction misrepresents the electrical activity of [[Neural oscillation|brainwaves]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Scientific American |date=June 2007 |volume=296 |issue=6 |pages=39 |title=The (Other) Secret |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0607-39|pmid=17663221 |last1=Shermer |first1=Michael }}</ref> [[Victor Stenger]] and [[Leon Lederman]] are critical of attempts to use [[quantum mysticism]] to bridge any unexplained or seemingly implausible effects, believing these to be traits of modern [[pseudoscience]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Stenger |first=Victor J. |title=Cosmic Mind |url=http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |publisher=University of Colorado |authorlink=Victor_Stenger |pages=8\u201319 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013317/http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"Leon Lederman 1993 189\u2013198\"/><ref name=\"plato.stanford.edu\"/>\n\nThe mantra of ''[[The Secret (book)|The Secret]]'', and by extension, the Law of Attraction, is as follows: positive thoughts and positive visualization will have a direct impact on the self. While positivity can improve one\u2019s quality of life and resilience through hardship <ref>{{cite journal |journal=International Journal of Medicine |date=2015|volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=24-28 |title=The effect of positive thinking on quality of life and resiliency of cancer patients |doi=10.17795/rijm27122|last1=Mousavi |first1=E|last2=Esmaeili|first2=A|last3=Saless |first3=S |doi-access=free }}</ref>, it can also be misguiding. Holding the belief that positive thinking will manifest positivity in one\u2019s life diminishes the value of hard work and perseverance, such as in the 1970s pursual of \u201cself-esteem-based education\u201d <ref>{{cite journal |journal=Skeptic |date=2009|volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=30-38 |title=Positively misguided: The myths and mistakes of the positive thinking movement|last1=Salerno |first1=S }}</ref>. The belief was that for students to succeed academically (and largely, in life), they must develop a positive sense of their own self-worth. The rationale behind this theory comes from the perspective that people who are successful are also generally positive when discussing their success (e.g., motivational speakers), therefore one\u2019s success must be related to how they view themselves. Thus, the American education system received a complete reconstruction to ensure students felt valued in their academic efforts. Grading curves were implemented so that fewer students were held back, honour rolls were removed to prevent lower-achieving individuals from feeling disappointed in themselves, and teachers could no longer grade assignments using red ink as this was viewed as \u201cstigmatizing\u201d <ref>{{cite journal |journal=Skeptic |date=2009|volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=30-38 |title=Positively misguided: The myths and mistakes of the positive thinking movement|last1=Salerno |first1=S }}</ref>. Students were no longer held to the same standard of achievement. It was later realized that this system was ultimately unsuccessful in promoting success; lower-achieving students who were advanced further into higher-level grades were unable, or unwilling to, garner an understanding of the curriculum. Thus, in spite of having grandiose self-value, student academic achievement was unable to match it. While empirical research has shown that there is an existing relationship between student self-worth and school achievement <ref>{{cite journal |journal=Personality and Individual Differences |date=2008|volume=45|pages=559-564 |title=Relations of academic and general self-esteem to school achievement|last1=Pullmann |first1=H |last2=Allik|first2=J }}</ref>, the motivation of students to work hard and achieve based on their own academic merit cannot be discounted.\n\n==Prominent supporters==\n\n* In 1891 Californian author and humorist [[Prentice Mulford]] used the term Law of Attraction in his essays ''Some Laws of Health and Beauty'' and ''Good And Ill Effects of Thought''.\n* In 1897 [[Ralph Waldo Trine]] wrote ''In Tune with the Infinite''. In the second paragraph of chapter 9 he writes, \"The Law of Attraction works unceasingly throughout the universe, and the one great and never changing fact in connection with it is, as we have found, that like attracts like.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Trine|first1=Ralph|title=In Tune With The Infinite|publisher=G Bell and Sons, LTD. Published 1911|location=London|page=174}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Troward]], a strong influence in the New Thought Movement, gave a 1904 lecture in which he claimed that thought precedes physical form and \"the action of Mind plants that nucleus which, if allowed to grow undisturbed, will eventually attract to itself all the conditions necessary for its manifestation in outward visible form.\"<ref>Judge Thomas Troward, ''The Edinburgh Lectures on Mental Science'', 1904.</ref>\n* In 1902 English New Thought writer [[James Allen (author)|James Allen]] (best known for writing ''[[As a Man Thinketh]]'') wrote a series of books and articles between 1901 and 1912, after which his wife [[Lily L. Allen|Lily]] continued his work.\n* [[Emmet Fox]] wrote about metaphysics and the power of prayer in essays and books. His teachings are founded in Christianity and bible stories. He cites Jesus Christ as being the greatest teacher of metaphysics who ever lived and explains that thoughts are our most important emanation, more important than what we say or what we do. In the books ''Power Through Constructive Thinking'' and ''Find and Use your Inner Power'' Fox speaks about \"building the mental equivalent of what you want and to expunge those that you don't\".\n* In his New Thought Movement book [[William Walker Atkinson]] used the phrase ''Thought Vibration or the Law of Attraction in the Thought World'' (1906), stating that \"like attracts like\".<ref>[http://gitacademy.tripod.com/GodsInTraining/ThoughtVibration.htm William Walker Atkinson. ''Thought Vibration or the Law of Attraction''. Advanced Thought Publishing. 1906.] Out of Copyright version</ref>\n*[[Bruce MacLelland]]'s ''Prosperity Through Thought Force'' (1907), a [[prosperity theology]] book, summarizes the principle as \"You are what you think, not what you think you are.\" It was published by [[Elizabeth Towne]], the editor of ''[[The Nautilus (magazine)|The Nautilus Magazine, a Journal of New Thought]]''.<ref name=\"maclelland\">MacLelland, Bruce, ''Prosperity Through Thought Force,'' Elizabeth Towne, 1907</ref>\n* In his 1910 ''The Science of Getting Rich'' [[Wallace D. Wattles]] espoused similar principles \u2014 that simply believing in the object of your desire and focusing on it will lead to that object or goal being realized on the material plane (Wattles claims in the Preface and later chapters of this book that his premise stems from the [[monistic]] [[Hindu]] view that God provides everything and can deliver what we focus on). The book also claims negative thinking will manifest negative results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Science_of_Getting_Rich |title=The Science of Getting Rich - Wikisource |publisher=En.wikisource.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n* [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophical]] author [[William Quan Judge]] used the phrase in ''The Ocean of Theosophy'' (1915).<ref>{{cite book|last= Judge | first = William Quan |title = The Ocean of Theosophy |publisher =United Lodge of Theosophists |year= 1915 | page = 103|isbn= 978-0-7661-0544-7 }}</ref>\n* Another theosophical author [[Annie Besant]] discussed the 'Law of Attraction' in 1919.<ref>{{cite web|title=POPULAR LECTURES ON THEOSOPHY|url=http://www.anandgholap.net/Popular_Lectures_On_Theosophy-AB.htm|publisher=anandgholap|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Besant compared her version of it to [[gravitation]], and said that the law represented a form of [[karma]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Karma|url=http://www.anandgholap.net/Karma-AB.htm|publisher= Theosophical Publishing House|accessdate=16 May 2012|author=Annie Besant|year=1895|edition= First}}</ref>\n* [[Napoleon Hill]] published two books on the theme. The first, ''[[The Law of Success|The Law of Success in 16 Lessons]]'' (1928), directly and repeatedly references the Law of Attraction and proposes that it operates by use of radio waves transmitted by the brain. The second, ''[[Think and Grow Rich]]'' (1937), went on to sell 100 million copies by 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Think and Grow Rich |url=http://www.naphill.org/shop/books/think-and-grow-rich/ |date=2015 |publisher=Napoleon Hill Foundation |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> Hill insisted on the importance of controlling one's own thoughts in order to achieve success, as well as the energy that thoughts have and their ability to attract other thoughts. He mentions a \"secret\" to success and promises to indirectly describe it at least once in every chapter. It is never named and he says that discovering it on one's own is far more beneficial. Many people have argued over what it<ref>{{cite web|title=Why The Law of Attraction has been a Secret|url=http://www.law-of-attraction.com/131/law-of-attraction-has-been-a-secret/|publisher=Positive Inspiration|access-date=15 May 2016|date=2016-04-06}}</ref> actually is, some claim it's the Law of Attraction. Hill states the \"secret\" is mentioned no fewer than a hundred times, yet reference to \"attract\" is used less than 30 times in the text. He further claims that people can obtain what they desire through thought of definite purpose.{{sfn|Hill|2010|pp=23-24}}\n* [[Israel Regardie]] published books with the Law of Attraction theme as one of his prevailing Universal Laws. In, ''The Art of True Healing: A Treatise on the Mechanism of Prayer and the Operation of the Law of Attraction in Nature'' (1937), he taught a focused meditation technique to help the mind to learn to heal itself on a physical and spiritual level. Regardie claimed that the Law of Attraction was a valid method for attracting good physical health and for improvement in any aspect of one's life.<ref name=\"Regardie 1974 p. \">{{cite book | last=Regardie | first=I. | title=The Art of True Healing: A Treatise on the Mechanism of Prayer and the Operation of the Law of Attraction in Nature | year=1974 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3-QumgEACAAJ | access-date=3 August 2018 | page=}}</ref>\n* In 1960 [[W. Clement Stone]] and Napoleon Hill co-wrote ''Success Through a Positive Mental Attitude''.<ref name=\"Hill Stone 1991 p. \">{{cite book | last=Hill | first=N. | last2=Stone | first2=W.C. | title=Success Through a Positive Mental Attitude | publisher=Pocket Books | year=1991 | isbn=978-0-671-74322-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DLzx4dWIO9EC | access-date=3 August 2018 | page=}}</ref>\n* In his 1988 ''The American Myth of Success'' Richard Weiss states that the principle of \"non-resistance\" is a popular concept of the New Thought movement and is taught in conjunction with the Law of Attraction.<ref>{{cite book|title=The American Myth of Success|publisher=Illini Books|pages=169}}</ref>\n* The 2008 [[Esther Hicks|Esther and Jerry Hicks']] book ''Money and the Law of Attraction: Learning to Attract Health, Wealth & Happiness'' appeared on the [[New York Times Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/31/books/bestseller/bestpaperadvice.html?_r=1&8bu&emc=bu&oref=slogin |title=New York Times Bestseller information August 31, 2008 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2008-08-31 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n* [[Rhonda Byrne]], author of ''[[The Secret (book)|The Secret]]'', ''[[The Power (self-help book)|The Power]]'' and ''[[The Magic (book)|The Magic]]'', was influenced by Wattles' ''The Science of Getting Rich''.<ref name=NEWSWEEK>{{cite news| author = Jerry Adler | url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/36603/output/print| title= Decoding The Secret | work= [[Newsweek]] | date = 2007-08-21 | accessdate = 3 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Conor McGregor]] has claimed to use the Law of Attraction. He said, \"This is what I dreamed into reality\", upon winning his second UFC championship title belt.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Review-Journal 2017\">{{cite web | title=Conor McGregor credits success to 'the law of attraction' | website=Las Vegas Review-Journal | date=25 August 2017 | url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/boxing/conor-mcgregor-credits-success-to-the-law-of-attraction/ | access-date=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Norman Vincent Peale]]<ref name=\"Prosperity Attraction \u2013 you create your own reality 2008\">{{cite web | title=Prosperity Attraction \u2013 you create your own reality \u00bb Norman Vincent Peale | website=Prosperity Attraction \u2013 you create your own reality | date=22 September 2008 | url=http://prosperity-attraction.com/category/norman-vincent-peale/ | access-date=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[List of New Thought writers]]\n* ''[[Conversations with God]]''\n* [[Cosmic ordering]]\n* [[Efficacy of prayer]]\n* [[Homophily]]\n* [[Internal locus of control]]\n* [[Kybalion]]\n* [[Law of contagion]]\n* [[Magical thinking]]\n* [[Medical students' disease]]\n* [[Mind over matter]]\n* [[Positive mental attitude]]\n* [[Priming (psychology)]]\n* [[Prosperity theology]]\n* [[Pygmalion effect]]\n* [[Quantum mysticism]]\n* [[Self-fulfilling prophecy]]\n* [[Sympathetic magic]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{wiktionary-inline}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|The Science of Getting Rich}}\n\n{{Pseudoscience|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Religious Science footer}}\n{{Unity footer}}\n{{Divine Science footer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Law Of Attraction}}\n[[Category:New Thought beliefs]]\n[[Category:Quantum mysticism]]\n[[Category:New Age]]\n[[Category:Magical thinking]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Law of attraction (disambiguation){{!}}Law of attraction}}\n{{New Thought beliefs}}\n{{Paranormal}}\nIn the [[New Thought]] philosophy, the '''Law of Attraction''' is the belief that positive or negative thoughts bring positive or negative experiences into a person's life.<ref name=gazette>Whittaker, S. [http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/story.html?id=78fc94dd-c0b2-4ade-891d-98770bfae388&k=70777 Secret attraction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090328/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/story.html?id=78fc94dd-c0b2-4ade-891d-98770bfae388&k=70777 |date=2016-03-04 }}, ''The Montreal Gazette'', May 12, 2007.</ref><ref>Redden, Guy, \"Magic Happens: A New Age Metaphysical Mystery Tour\", ''Journal of Australian Studies'': 101</ref> The belief is based on the ideas that people and their thoughts are made from \"pure energy\", and that a process of like energy attracting like energy exists through which a person can improve their health, wealth, and personal relationships. There is zero empirical scientific evidence supporting the law of attraction, and it is widely considered a pseudoscience. \n\nAdvocates generally combine [[cognitive reframing]] techniques with affirmations and [[creative visualization]] to replace limiting or self-destructive (\"negative\") thoughts with more empowered, adaptive (\"positive\") thoughts. A key component of the philosophy is the idea that in order to effectively change one's negative thinking patterns, one must also \"feel\" (through [[creative visualization]]) that the desired changes have already occurred. This combination of positive thought and positive emotion is believed to allow one to attract positive experiences and opportunities by achieving resonance with the proposed energetic law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelawofattraction.com/what-is-the-law-of-attraction/|title=What Is The Law Of Attraction|last1=Hurst|first1=Katherine|date=|website=The Law Of Attraction|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe Law of Attraction has no scientific basis<ref name=\"Scientific American\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Shermer | first = Michael\n  | authorlink = Michael Shermer\n  | title = The (Other) Secret\n  | journal = [[Scientific American]]\n  | volume = 296\n  | issue = 6\n  | pages = 39\n  | date = 1 June 2007\n  | doi = 10.1038/scientificamerican0607-39\n  | pmid = 17663221\n }}</ref> and has been dubbed a [[pseudoscience]].<ref name=\"Live Science\">{{cite web\n  | last = Radford | first = Benjamin\n  | authorlink = Benjamin Radford\n  | title = The Pseudoscience of 'The Secret'\n  | work = [[Live Science]]\n  | date = 3 February 2009\n  | url = http://www.livescience.com/5303-pseudoscience-secret.html\n  | accessdate = 31 March 2017\n}}</ref> A number of researchers have criticized the misuse of scientific concepts by its proponents.<ref name=\"Scientific American\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Stenger |first=Victor J. |title=Cosmic Mind |url=http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |publisher=University of Colorado |authorlink=Victor_Stenger |pages=8\u201319 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013317/http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"Leon Lederman 1993 189\u2013198\">{{cite book |title=The God Particle: If the Universe is the Answer, What is the Question |pages=189\u2013198 |author=Leon Lederman |author2=Dick Teresi |date=1993 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company}}</ref><ref name=\"plato.stanford.edu\">[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/pseudo-science/#NonSciPosSci Non-science posing as science; Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[New Thought]] movement grew out of the teachings of [[Phineas Quimby]] in the early 19th century. Early in his life, Quimby was diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]]. Early 19th century medicine had no reliable cure for tuberculosis. Quimby took to horse riding and noted that intense excitement temporarily relieved him from his affliction. This method for relieving his pain and seemingly subsequent recovery prompted Phineas to pursue a study of \"Mind over Body\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hughes|first1=n|title=Phineas Parkhurst Quimby|url=http://phineasquimby.wwwhubs.com/|accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref>  Although he never used the words \"Law of Attraction\", he explained this in a statement that captured the concept in the field of health: {{quote|the trouble is in the mind, for the body is only the house for the mind to dwell in, and we put a value on it according to its worth. Therefore if your mind has been deceived by some invisible enemy into a belief, you have put it into the form of a disease, with or without your knowledge. By my theory or truth, I come in contact with your enemy and restore you to your health and happiness. This I do partly mentally and partly by talking till I correct the wrong impressions and establish the Truth, and the Truth is the cure.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Quimby Manuscripts|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/quimbyPhineas/manuscripts/pages/quimby-manuscripts-194.htm|publisher=New Thought library|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\nIn 1877, the term \"Law of Attraction\" appeared in print for the first time in a book written by the Russian occultist [[Helena Blavatsky]], in a context alluding to an attractive power existing between elements of spirit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isis Unveiled|url=http://www.theosociety.org/pasadena/isis/iu1-10.htm|publisher=Theosophical University Press, page 340|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first articulator of the Law as general principle was [[Prentice Mulford]]. Mulford, a pivotal figure in the development of New Thought thinking, discusses the Law of Attraction at length in his essay \"The Law of Success\",<ref>{{cite book|title=Your Forces and How to Use Them, Vol. 1|url=https://archive.org/stream/yourforcesandho09mulfgoog#page/n66/mode/2up|publisher=New York, F.J. Needham|year=1888}}</ref> published 1886-1887. In this, Mulford was followed by other New Thought authors, such as Henry Wood (starting with his ''God\u2019s Image in Man'',<ref>{{cite book|title=God's Image in Man, Ch. 6, \"The Universality of Law\"|url=https://archive.org/stream/godsimageinmans01woodgoog#page/n134/mode/2up|publisher=Lee and Shepard Publishers, 1892}}</ref> 1892), and [[Ralph Waldo Trine]] (starting with his first book, ''What All the World's A-Seeking'',<ref>{{cite book|title=What All the World's A-Seeking|url=https://archive.org/details/whatallworldsas00tringoog|publisher=New Canaan, Conn., Keats Pub|year=1973}}</ref> 1896). For these authors, the Law of Attraction is concerned not only about health but every aspect of life.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Tune With The Infinite|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/trineRalphWaldo/inTune/pages/in-tune-with-the-infinite-026.htm#TopOfText|publisher=New Thought Library|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE GOD IN YOU|url=http://prenticemulford.wwwhubs.com/tgiy.htm|publisher=Cornerstone Publishing, 2001|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 20th century saw a surge in interest in the subject with many books being written about it, amongst which are two of the [[List of best-selling books|best-selling books]] of all time; ''[[Think and Grow Rich]]'' (1937) by [[Napoleon Hill]], ''[[The Power of Positive Thinking]]'' (1952) by [[Norman Vincent Peale]], and ''[[You Can Heal Your Life]]'' (1984) by [[Louise Hay]]. The [[Esther Hicks|Abraham-Hicks]] material is based primarily around the Law of Attraction.\n\nIn 2006, the concept of the Law of Attraction gained renewed exposure with the release of the film ''[[The Secret (2006 film)|The Secret]]'' (2006) which was then developed into a book of the same title in 2007. The movie and book gained widespread media coverage.<ref name=gazette /><ref name=oprah1>{{cite web |url= http://www.oprah.com/spirit/The-Law-of-Attraction-Real-Life-Stories_1 |title=The Law of Attraction: Real-Life Stories - Oprah.com |work=oprah.com |accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref><ref name=oprah2>{{cite web |url= http://www.oprah.com/spirit/Go-Beyond-The-Secret_1 |title=Go Beyond 'The Secret' - Oprah.com |work=oprah.com |accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref> This was followed by a sequel, ''[[The Power (self-help book)|The Power]]'' in 2010 that talks about the law of attraction being the law of love.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Business/power-author-rhonda-byrnes-book/story?id=11421349|title=The Secret Is Out: Megahit Writer Says Power of Love Will Fill Your Bank Account|last=NANCE-NASH|first=SHERYL|date=August 18, 2010|work=ABC News|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Descriptions==\nProponents believe that the Law of Attraction is always in operation and that it brings to each person the conditions and experiences that they predominantly think about, or which they desire or expect.\n\n[[Charles F. Haanel|Charles Haanel]] wrote in ''[[The Master Key System]]'' (1912):\n{{quote|The law of attraction will certainly and unerringly bring to you the conditions, environment, and experiences in life, corresponding with your habitual, characteristic, predominant mental attitude.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Master Key System. Chapter 8, part 18.|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/haanel-charles/Master-Key-System/audioEbook/master-key-systemRAW.pdf|publisher=New Thought Library|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\n[[Ralph Waldo Trine|Ralph Trine]] wrote in ''In Tune With The Infinite'' (1897):\n{{quote|The law of attraction works universally on every plane of action, and we attract whatever we desire or expect. If we desire one thing and expect another, we become like houses divided against themselves, which are quickly brought to desolation. Determine resolutely to expect only what you desire, then you will attract only what you wish for.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Tune With The Infinite, by Ralph Trine|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/trineRalphWaldo/inTune/pages/in-tune-with-the-infinite-035.htm#TopOfText|publisher=New Thought Library|accessdate=18 June 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nIn her 2006 film ''[[The Secret (2006 film)|The Secret]]'', Rhonda Byrne emphasized thinking about what each person wants to obtain, but also to infuse the thought with the maximum possible amount of emotion. She claims the combination of thought and feeling is what attracts the desire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tameyourmind.org/articles/how-can-it-possibly-be-law-attraction-works|title=How can it possibly be that the law of attraction works?|last=Henry|first=Juliette|date=|website=www.tameyourmind.org|publisher=Transformation guide|access-date=3 Dec 2016}}</ref> Another similar book is [[James Redfield]]'s ''[[The Celestine Prophecy]]'', which says reality can be manifested by man.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Redfield|first1=James|title=The Celestine Prophecy: An Adventure|date=1993|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York}}</ref> ''The Power of Your Subconscious Mind'' by Joseph Murphy, says readers can achieve seemingly impossible goals by learning how to bring the mind itself under control. ''The Power'' by Rhonda Byrne, ''The Alchemist'' by [[Paulo Coelho]], and ''The Power of Now'' by [[Eckhart Tolle]] are similar. While personal testimonies claim the secret and the law to have worked for them, a number of skeptics have criticized Byrne's film and book. ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' called the secret pseudoscience and an \"illusion of knowledge\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chabris|first1=Christopher F.|last2=Simons|first2=Daniel J.|title=The Pseudoscience of \u2018The Secret\u2019 and \u2018The Power\u2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/26/books/review/Chabris-t.html|accessdate=2017-08-13|work=The New York Times|date=24 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Philosophical and religious basis==\nThe New Thought concept of the Law of Attraction is rooted in ideas that come from various philosophical and religious traditions.  In particular, it has been inspired by [[Hermeticism]], [[New England transcendentalism]], specific verses from the [[Bible]], and [[Hinduism]]. \n<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melanson|first1=Terry|title=Oprah Winfrey, New Thought, \"The Secret\" and the \"New Alchemy\" |url=http://www.conspiracyarchive.com/2014/07/20/oprah-winfrey-new-thought-the-secret-and-the-new-alchemy/|publisher=Conspiracy Archive|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Aoust|first1=Maja|title=The Secret Source|date=2012|publisher=Process|isbn=978-1-934170-32-8|page=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Zink|first1=Robert|title=Magical Energy Healing: The Ruach Healing Method|date=2014|publisher=Law of Attraction Solutions, Llc|isbn=978-0990825036|page=299|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6kJ8BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA299&lpg=PA299&dq=%22law+of+attraction%22+%22emerald+tablet%22#v=onepage&q=%22law%20of%20attraction%22%20%22emerald%20tablet%22&f=false|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Donker|first1=Gerald|title=Exposing the Secret Law of Attraction|date=2008|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1409236146|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sCsqAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27&dq=%22the+new+thought%22+%22law+of+attraction%22+bible#v=onepage&q=%22the%20new%20thought%22%20%22law%20of%20attraction%22%20bible&f=false|accessdate=6 November 2015}}{{self-published source|date={{subst:CURRENTMONTH}}{{subst:CURRENTYEAR}}}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harrold|first1=Glenn|title=The Answer: Supercharge the Law of Attraction and Find the Secret of True Happiness|date=2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-1409112716|url=https://books.google.com/?id=N917eoI9LzcC&pg=PT50&lpg=PT50&dq=%22law+of+attraction%22+hinduism+%22new+thought%22#v=onepage&q=%22law%20of%20attraction%22%20hinduism%20%22new%20thought%22&f=false|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=James|first1=William|title=The Varieties of Religious Experience|date=1902|publisher=Longmans Green & Co|isbn=978-1439297278|page=94|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UPLBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=william+James+%22mind-cure+is+the%22#v=onepage&q=william%20James%20%22mind-cure%20is%20the%22&f=false|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHermeticism influenced the development of European thought in the [[Renaissance]]. Its ideas were transmitted partly through [[alchemy]]. In the 18th century, [[Franz Mesmer]] studied the works of alchemists such as [[Paracelsus]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Aoust|first1=Maja|title=The Secret Source|date=2012|publisher=Process|isbn=978-1-934170-32-8|page=16}}</ref> and [[Jan Baptist van Helmont|van Helmont]].<ref name=Hist/> Van Helmont was a 17th-century [[Flemish people|Flemish]] physician who proclaimed the curative powers of the imagination.<ref name=Hist/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hedesan|first1=Georgiana D.|title=Paracelsian Medicine and Theory of Generation in 'Exterior homo', a Manuscript Probably Authored by Jan Baptist Van Helmont (1579\u20131644), ref 52|journal=Medical History|date=July 2014|volume=58|issue=3|pmc=4103403|pmid=25045180|doi=10.1017/mdh.2014.29|pages=375\u201396}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hedesan|first1=Delia Georgiana|title='Christian Philosophy': Medical Alchemy and Christian Thought in the Work of Jan Baptista Van Helmont (1579-1644)|date=2012|page= 31|url=https://ore.exeter.ac.uk/repository/bitstream/handle/10036/4083/HedesanD.pdf?sequence=4|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> This lead Mesmer to develop his ideas about [[Animal magnetism]] which [[Phineas Quimby]], the founder of New Thought, studied.<ref name=Hist>{{cite web|last1=Braden|first1=Charles S.|title=A BRIEF HISTORY OF THE NEW THOUGHT MOVEMENT.(1963)|url=http://www.surrenderworks.com/library/downloads/braden.pdf|publisher=surrenderworks.com|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=PHINEAS PARKHURST QUIMBY 1802 - 1866 Father of New Thought|url=http://phineasquimby.wwwhubs.com/|publisher=phineasquimby|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Transcendentalist movement developed in the United States immediately before the emergence of New Thought and is thought to have had a great influence on it. [[George Ripley (transcendentalist)|George Ripley]], an important figure in that movement, stated that its leading idea was \"the supremacy of mind over matter\".<ref name=Hist/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mikics|first1=David|title=The Annotated Emerson|date=2012|publisher=Belknap Press|isbn=978-0674049239|page=6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nI3uBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA6&lpg=PA6&dq=%22george+ripley%22+%22the+supremacy+of+mind+over+matter%22#v=onepage&q=%22george%20ripley%22%20%22the%20supremacy%20of%20mind%20over%20matter%22&f=false|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNew Thought authors often quote certain verses from the Bible in the context of the Law of Attraction. An example is [[Mark 11]]:24: \"Therefore I tell you, whatever you ask in prayer, believe that you have received it, and it will be yours.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark 11:24|url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=mark+11%3A24&version=RSV|publisher=Bible Gateway|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Master Key System, by Charles Haanel (1912). Chapter 11, section 17|url=http://newthoughtlibrary.com/haanel-charles/Master-Key-System/audioEbook/master-key-systemRAW.pdf|publisher=The New Thought Library|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=secr>{{cite book|last1=Byrne|first1=Rhonda|title=The Secret|date=2006|publisher=Beyond Words|isbn=978-1-58270-170-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/secretbyrn00byrn/page/54 54]|url=https://archive.org/details/secretbyrn00byrn/page/54}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century [[Swami Vivekananda]] traveled to the United States and gave lectures on [[Hinduism]]. These talks greatly influenced the New Thought movement and in particular, [[William Walker Atkinson]] who was one of New Thought's pioneers.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Aoust|first1=Maja|title=The Secret Source|date=2012|publisher=Process|isbn=978-1-934170-32-8|page=61}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Woodroffe|first1=John|title=Shakti and Sh\u00e2kta, Chapter 24, 12th paragraph|date=1918|publisher=Luzac & Co|isbn=978-1595479204|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/tantra/sas/sas24.htm|\naccessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'' magazine criticized the lack of [[falsifiability]] and [[testability]] of these claims.<ref name=\"csicop.org\">{{cite web|author1=Mary Carmichael |author2=Ben Radford |url=http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/secrets_and_lies/ |title=CSI &#124; Secrets and Lies |publisher=Csicop.org |date= |accessdate=2012-05-16}}</ref> Critics have asserted that the evidence provided is usually [[anecdotal]] and that, because of the [[publication bias|self-selecting nature of the positive reports]], as well as the [[Subjectivity|subjective]] nature of any results, these reports are susceptible to [[confirmation bias]] and [[selection bias]].<ref name=\"Kaptchuck\">{{cite journal |author=Kaptchuk, T., & Eisenberg, D. |year=1998 |title=The Persuasive Appeal of Alternative Medicine |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=129 |issue=12 |pmid=9867762 |pages=1061\u20135 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-129-12-199812150-00011|last2=Eisenberg |citeseerx=10.1.1.694.4798 }}</ref> Physicist [[Ali Alousi]], for instance, criticized it as unmeasurable and questioned the likelihood that thoughts can affect anything outside the head.<ref name=gazette/>\n\nThe Law of Attraction has been popularized in the early 21st century by books and films such as ''[[The Secret (book)|The Secret]]''. This 2006 film and the subsequent book<ref>{{cite book |title=The Secret |year=2006 |first=Rhonda |last=Byrne |publisher=Beyond Words Publishing |isbn=978-1-58270-170-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/secretbyrn00byrn }}</ref> use interviews with New Thought authors and speakers to explain the principles of the proposed metaphysical law that one can attract anything that one thinks about consistently. Writing for the Committee for Skeptical Inquiry, [[Mary Carmichael]] and [[Ben Radford]] wrote that \"neither the film nor the book has any basis in scientific reality\", and that its premise contains \"an ugly flipside: if you have an accident or disease, it's your fault\".<ref name=\"csicop.org\"/>\n\nOthers have questioned the references to modern scientific theory, and have maintained, for example, that the Law of Attraction misrepresents the electrical activity of [[Neural oscillation|brainwaves]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Scientific American |date=June 2007 |volume=296 |issue=6 |pages=39 |title=The (Other) Secret |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0607-39|pmid=17663221 |last1=Shermer |first1=Michael }}</ref> [[Victor Stenger]] and [[Leon Lederman]] are critical of attempts to use [[quantum mysticism]] to bridge any unexplained or seemingly implausible effects, believing these to be traits of modern [[pseudoscience]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Stenger |first=Victor J. |title=Cosmic Mind |url=http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |publisher=University of Colorado |authorlink=Victor_Stenger |pages=8\u201319 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013317/http://www.colorado.edu/philosophy/vstenger/Quantum/01CosmicMind.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"Leon Lederman 1993 189\u2013198\"/><ref name=\"plato.stanford.edu\"/>\n\nThe mantra of ''[[The Secret (book)|The Secret]]'', and by extension, the Law of Attraction, is as follows: positive thoughts and positive visualization will have a direct impact on the self. While positivity can improve one\u2019s quality of life and resilience through hardship <ref>{{cite journal |journal=International Journal of Medicine |date=2015|volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=24-28 |title=The effect of positive thinking on quality of life and resiliency of cancer patients |doi=10.17795/rijm27122|last1=Mousavi |first1=E|last2=Esmaeili|first2=A|last3=Saless |first3=S |doi-access=free }}</ref>, it can also be misguiding. Holding the belief that positive thinking will manifest positivity in one\u2019s life diminishes the value of hard work and perseverance, such as in the 1970s pursual of \u201cself-esteem-based education\u201d <ref>{{cite journal |journal=Skeptic |date=2009|volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=30-38 |title=Positively misguided: The myths and mistakes of the positive thinking movement|last1=Salerno |first1=S }}</ref>. The belief was that for students to succeed academically (and largely, in life), they must develop a positive sense of their own self-worth. The rationale behind this theory comes from the perspective that people who are successful are also generally positive when discussing their success (e.g., motivational speakers), therefore one\u2019s success must be related to how they view themselves. Thus, the American education system received a complete reconstruction to ensure students felt valued in their academic efforts. Grading curves were implemented so that fewer students were held back, honour rolls were removed to prevent lower-achieving individuals from feeling disappointed in themselves, and teachers could no longer grade assignments using red ink as this was viewed as \u201cstigmatizing\u201d <ref>{{cite journal |journal=Skeptic |date=2009|volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=30-38 |title=Positively misguided: The myths and mistakes of the positive thinking movement|last1=Salerno |first1=S }}</ref>. Students were no longer held to the same standard of achievement. It was later realized that this system was ultimately unsuccessful in promoting success; lower-achieving students who were advanced further into higher-level grades were unable, or unwilling to, garner an understanding of the curriculum. Thus, in spite of having grandiose self-value, student academic achievement was unable to match it. While empirical research has shown that there is an existing relationship between student self-worth and school achievement <ref>{{cite journal |journal=Personality and Individual Differences |date=2008|volume=45|pages=559-564 |title=Relations of academic and general self-esteem to school achievement|last1=Pullmann |first1=H |last2=Allik|first2=J }}</ref>, the motivation of students to work hard and achieve based on their own academic merit cannot be discounted.\n\n==Prominent supporters==\n\n* In 1891 Californian author and humorist [[Prentice Mulford]] used the term Law of Attraction in his essays ''Some Laws of Health and Beauty'' and ''Good And Ill Effects of Thought''.\n* In 1897 [[Ralph Waldo Trine]] wrote ''In Tune with the Infinite''. In the second paragraph of chapter 9 he writes, \"The Law of Attraction works unceasingly throughout the universe, and the one great and never changing fact in connection with it is, as we have found, that like attracts like.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Trine|first1=Ralph|title=In Tune With The Infinite|publisher=G Bell and Sons, LTD. Published 1911|location=London|page=174}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Troward]], a strong influence in the New Thought Movement, gave a 1904 lecture in which he claimed that thought precedes physical form and \"the action of Mind plants that nucleus which, if allowed to grow undisturbed, will eventually attract to itself all the conditions necessary for its manifestation in outward visible form.\"<ref>Judge Thomas Troward, ''The Edinburgh Lectures on Mental Science'', 1904.</ref>\n* In 1902 English New Thought writer [[James Allen (author)|James Allen]] (best known for writing ''[[As a Man Thinketh]]'') wrote a series of books and articles between 1901 and 1912, after which his wife [[Lily L. Allen|Lily]] continued his work.\n* [[Emmet Fox]] wrote about metaphysics and the power of prayer in essays and books. His teachings are founded in Christianity and bible stories. He cites Jesus Christ as being the greatest teacher of metaphysics who ever lived and explains that thoughts are our most important emanation, more important than what we say or what we do. In the books ''Power Through Constructive Thinking'' and ''Find and Use your Inner Power'' Fox speaks about \"building the mental equivalent of what you want and to expunge those that you don't\".\n* In his New Thought Movement book [[William Walker Atkinson]] used the phrase ''Thought Vibration or the Law of Attraction in the Thought World'' (1906), stating that \"like attracts like\".<ref>[http://gitacademy.tripod.com/GodsInTraining/ThoughtVibration.htm William Walker Atkinson. ''Thought Vibration or the Law of Attraction''. Advanced Thought Publishing. 1906.] Out of Copyright version</ref>\n*[[Bruce MacLelland]]'s ''Prosperity Through Thought Force'' (1907), a [[prosperity theology]] book, summarizes the principle as \"You are what you think, not what you think you are.\" It was published by [[Elizabeth Towne]], the editor of ''[[The Nautilus (magazine)|The Nautilus Magazine, a Journal of New Thought]]''.<ref name=\"maclelland\">MacLelland, Bruce, ''Prosperity Through Thought Force,'' Elizabeth Towne, 1907</ref>\n* In his 1910 ''The Science of Getting Rich'' [[Wallace D. Wattles]] espoused similar principles \u2014 that simply believing in the object of your desire and focusing on it will lead to that object or goal being realized on the material plane (Wattles claims in the Preface and later chapters of this book that his premise stems from the [[monistic]] [[Hindu]] view that God provides everything and can deliver what we focus on). The book also claims negative thinking will manifest negative results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Science_of_Getting_Rich |title=The Science of Getting Rich - Wikisource |publisher=En.wikisource.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n* [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophical]] author [[William Quan Judge]] used the phrase in ''The Ocean of Theosophy'' (1915).<ref>{{cite book|last= Judge | first = William Quan |title = The Ocean of Theosophy |publisher =United Lodge of Theosophists |year= 1915 | page = 103|isbn= 978-0-7661-0544-7 }}</ref>\n* Another theosophical author [[Annie Besant]] discussed the 'Law of Attraction' in 1919.<ref>{{cite web|title=POPULAR LECTURES ON THEOSOPHY|url=http://www.anandgholap.net/Popular_Lectures_On_Theosophy-AB.htm|publisher=anandgholap|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Besant compared her version of it to [[gravitation]], and said that the law represented a form of [[karma]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Karma|url=http://www.anandgholap.net/Karma-AB.htm|publisher= Theosophical Publishing House|accessdate=16 May 2012|author=Annie Besant|year=1895|edition= First}}</ref>\n* [[Napoleon Hill]] published two books on the theme. The first, ''[[The Law of Success|The Law of Success in 16 Lessons]]'' (1928), directly and repeatedly references the Law of Attraction and proposes that it operates by use of radio waves transmitted by the brain. The second, ''[[Think and Grow Rich]]'' (1937), went on to sell 100 million copies by 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Think and Grow Rich |url=http://www.naphill.org/shop/books/think-and-grow-rich/ |date=2015 |publisher=Napoleon Hill Foundation |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> Hill insisted on the importance of controlling one's own thoughts in order to achieve success, as well as the energy that thoughts have and their ability to attract other thoughts. He mentions a \"secret\" to success and promises to indirectly describe it at least once in every chapter. It is never named and he says that discovering it on one's own is far more beneficial. Many people have argued over what it<ref>{{cite web|title=Why The Law of Attraction has been a Secret|url=http://www.law-of-attraction.com/131/law-of-attraction-has-been-a-secret/|publisher=Positive Inspiration|access-date=15 May 2016|date=2016-04-06}}</ref> actually is, some claim it's the Law of Attraction. Hill states the \"secret\" is mentioned no fewer than a hundred times, yet reference to \"attract\" is used less than 30 times in the text. He further claims that people can obtain what they desire through thought of definite purpose.{{sfn|Hill|2010|pp=23-24}}\n* [[Israel Regardie]] published books with the Law of Attraction theme as one of his prevailing Universal Laws. In, ''The Art of True Healing: A Treatise on the Mechanism of Prayer and the Operation of the Law of Attraction in Nature'' (1937), he taught a focused meditation technique to help the mind to learn to heal itself on a physical and spiritual level. Regardie claimed that the Law of Attraction was a valid method for attracting good physical health and for improvement in any aspect of one's life.<ref name=\"Regardie 1974 p. \">{{cite book | last=Regardie | first=I. | title=The Art of True Healing: A Treatise on the Mechanism of Prayer and the Operation of the Law of Attraction in Nature | year=1974 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3-QumgEACAAJ | access-date=3 August 2018 | page=}}</ref>\n* In 1960 [[W. Clement Stone]] and Napoleon Hill co-wrote ''Success Through a Positive Mental Attitude''.<ref name=\"Hill Stone 1991 p. \">{{cite book | last=Hill | first=N. | last2=Stone | first2=W.C. | title=Success Through a Positive Mental Attitude | publisher=Pocket Books | year=1991 | isbn=978-0-671-74322-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DLzx4dWIO9EC | access-date=3 August 2018 | page=}}</ref>\n* In his 1988 ''The American Myth of Success'' Richard Weiss states that the principle of \"non-resistance\" is a popular concept of the New Thought movement and is taught in conjunction with the Law of Attraction.<ref>{{cite book|title=The American Myth of Success|publisher=Illini Books|pages=169}}</ref>\n* The 2008 [[Esther Hicks|Esther and Jerry Hicks']] book ''Money and the Law of Attraction: Learning to Attract Health, Wealth & Happiness'' appeared on the [[New York Times Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/31/books/bestseller/bestpaperadvice.html?_r=1&8bu&emc=bu&oref=slogin |title=New York Times Bestseller information August 31, 2008 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2008-08-31 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n* [[Rhonda Byrne]], author of ''[[The Secret (book)|The Secret]]'', ''[[The Power (self-help book)|The Power]]'' and ''[[The Magic (book)|The Magic]]'', was influenced by Wattles' ''The Science of Getting Rich''.<ref name=NEWSWEEK>{{cite news| author = Jerry Adler | url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/36603/output/print| title= Decoding The Secret | work= [[Newsweek]] | date = 2007-08-21 | accessdate = 3 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Conor McGregor]] has claimed to use the Law of Attraction. He said, \"This is what I dreamed into reality\", upon winning his second UFC championship title belt.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Review-Journal 2017\">{{cite web | title=Conor McGregor credits success to 'the law of attraction' | website=Las Vegas Review-Journal | date=25 August 2017 | url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/boxing/conor-mcgregor-credits-success-to-the-law-of-attraction/ | access-date=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Norman Vincent Peale]]<ref name=\"Prosperity Attraction \u2013 you create your own reality 2008\">{{cite web | title=Prosperity Attraction \u2013 you create your own reality \u00bb Norman Vincent Peale | website=Prosperity Attraction \u2013 you create your own reality | date=22 September 2008 | url=http://prosperity-attraction.com/category/norman-vincent-peale/ | access-date=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[List of New Thought writers]]\n* ''[[Conversations with God]]''\n* [[Cosmic ordering]]\n* [[Efficacy of prayer]]\n* [[Homophily]]\n* [[Internal locus of control]]\n* [[Kybalion]]\n* [[Law of contagion]]\n* [[Magical thinking]]\n* [[Medical students' disease]]\n* [[Mind over matter]]\n* [[Positive mental attitude]]\n* [[Priming (psychology)]]\n* [[Prosperity theology]]\n* [[Pygmalion effect]]\n* [[Quantum mysticism]]\n* [[Self-fulfilling prophecy]]\n* [[Sympathetic magic]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{wiktionary-inline}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|The Science of Getting Rich}}\n\n{{Pseudoscience|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Religious Science footer}}\n{{Unity footer}}\n{{Divine Science footer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Law Of Attraction}}\n[[Category:New Thought beliefs]]\n[[Category:Quantum mysticism]]\n[[Category:New Age]]\n[[Category:Magical thinking]]\n", "name_user": "Abhis33", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I have changed the link .)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_attraction_(New_Thought)"}
{"title_page": "Social psychology (sociology)", "text_new": "{{About|the subfield of sociology|the subfield of psychology|social psychology}}{{Hatnote|See also: [[microsociology]]}}\n{{Sociology}}\n\nIn [[sociology]], '''social psychology''' (also known as '''sociological social psychology''')<ref>\"[https://psychology.iresearchnet.com/social-psychology/sociological-social-psychology/ Sociological Social Psychology | Social Psychology].\" ''Psychology''. iResearchNet.</ref> is an area of sociology that focuses on [[social actions|social action]] and on the interrelation of [[personality]], [[Value (personal and cultural)|values]], and [[mind]] with [[social structure]] and [[culture]]. Some of the major topics in this field include [[social status]], structural \npower, [[Social change|sociocultural change]], [[social inequality]] and [[prejudice]], [[leadership]] and [[Group behaviour|intra-group behavior]], [[Social exchange theory|social exchange]], [[group conflict]], [[impression formation]] and [[Impression management|management]], [[Conversation analysis|conversation structures]], [[socialization]], [[social constructionism]], [[Norm (social)|social norms]] and [[Deviance (sociology)|deviance]], [[Identity (social science)|identity]] and [[role]]s, and [[emotional labor]]. \n\nThe primary methods of data collection are [[Sampling (statistics)|sample surveys]], [[Observational study|field observations]], [[Vignette (psychology)|vignette studies]], [[field experiment]]s, and [[Design of experiments|controlled experiments]].\n\n== History ==\nSociological social psychology emerged in 1902 with a landmark study by sociologist [[Charles Cooley]], entitled ''Human Nature and the Social Order'', which presented Cooley's concept of the [[Looking-glass self|''looking-glass self'']]. The first textbook in social psychology by a sociologist appeared in 1908: ''Social Psychology'' by [[Edward Alsworth Ross]]. The area's main journal was founded as ''Sociometry'' by [[Jacob L. Moreno]] in 1937, however its name would change to ''Social Psychology'' in 1978, and to ''[[Social Psychology Quarterly]]'' in 1979.\n\nIn the 1920s, [[W. I. Thomas]] contributed the notion of the [[definition of the situation|''definition of the situation'']], with a proposition, referred to as ''the'' ''[[Thomas theorem]]'', that became a basic tenet of sociology and sociological social psychology: \"if men define situations as real, they are real in their consequences.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOne of the major currents of theory in this area sprang from work by philosopher and sociologist [[George Herbert Mead]] at the [[University of Chicago]] from 1894 forward.  Mead generally is credited as the founder of [[symbolic interactionism]]. Mead's colleague and disciple at Chicago, sociologist [[Herbert Blumer]], coined the name of the framework in 1937.\n\nSociologist [[Talcott Parsons]], at [[Harvard University]] from 1927 forward, developed a [[Cybernetics|cybernetic]] [[Action theory (sociology)|theory of action]] which was adapted to [[Communication in small groups|small group research]] by Parsons' student and colleague, [[Robert Freed Bales]], resulting in a body of observational studies of [[Social relation|social interaction]] in groups using Bales' behavior coding scheme, Interaction Process Analysis.<ref>Bales, Robert Freed (1950), ''Interaction Process Analysis'', New York: Addison-Wesley. Some studies using the method are included in Hare, A. Paul, Edgar F. Borgatta, & R. F. Bales (1955), ''Small Groups: Studies in Social Interaction'', New York: Alfred A. Knopf.</ref> During his 41-year tenure at Harvard, Bales mentored a distinguished group of sociological social psychologists concerned with [[Group dynamics|group processes]] and other topics in sociological social psychology.<ref>See the list of Bales' students at pages 332-3 of R. F. Bales (1999), ''Social Interaction Systems: Theory and Measurement'', New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction.</ref>\n\n==Major frameworks==\n\n=== Symbolic interactionism ===\n{{main|Symbolic interactionism}}\nContemporary symbolic interactionism originated out of ideas of George Herbert Mead and [[Max Weber]]. In this framework meanings are constructed during social interaction, and constructed meanings influence the process of social interaction. Many symbolic interactionists see the self as a core meaning constructed through social relations, and influencing social relations.\n\nThe structural school of symbolic interactionism uses shared social knowledge from a [[Macrosociology|macro-level]] [[culture]], [[natural language]], [[Institution|social institution]], or [[organization]] to explain relatively enduring patterns of social interaction and psychology at the [[Microsociology|micro-level]], typically investigating these matters with [[Quantitative research|quantitative methods]]. Identity theory,<ref>[[Sheldon Stryker|Stryker, Sheldon]], & Burke, Peter J. (2000). \"The past, present, and future of an identity theory\". ''Social Psychology Quarterly'' '''63''': 284\u2013297. Burke, P. J., and Jan E. Stets (2009). ''Identity Theory'', New York, Oxford University Press.</ref> [[affect control theory]],<ref>Heise, David R. (1979). ''Understanding Events: Affect and the Construction of Social Action'', New York: Cambridge University Press. MacKinnon, N. J. (1994). ''Symbolic Interactionism as Affect Control'', Albany, NY, State University of New York Press. Heise, D. R. (2007). ''Expressive Orider: Confirming Sentiments in Social Actions'', New York, Springer.</ref> and the Iowa School<ref>Miller, Dan E. (2011). \"Toward a Theory of Interaction: The Iowa School,\" ''Symbolic Interaction'' '''34''': 340-348.</ref> are major programs of research in this tradition. Identity Theory and Affect Control Theory both focus on how actions control mental states, thereby manifesting the underlying cybernetic nature of the approach, evident in Mead's writings<ref>MacKinnon, Neil J. (1994). ''Symbolic Interactionism as Affect Control'', Albany, NY, State University of New York Press. Pp. 3-5.</ref> Affect Control Theory provides a [[mathematical model]] of [[role theory]] and of [[labeling theory]].\n\nProcess symbolic interactionism stems from the [[Chicago school (sociology)|Chicago School]] and considers the meanings underlying social interactions to be situated, creative, fluid, and often contested. Researchers in this tradition frequently use [[qualitative research|qualitative]] and [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] methods. A journal, ''Symbolic Interaction'', was founded in 1977 by the Society for the Study of Symbolic Interaction as a central outlet for the empirical research and [[Conceptual system|conceptual studies]] produced by scholars in this area.\n\n[[Postmodernism|Postmodern]] symbolic interactionists understand the notions of self and identity to be increasingly fragmented and illusory, and consider attempts at theorizing to be [[meta-narrative]]s with no more authority than other conversations. The approach is presented in detail by ''The SAGE Handbook of Qualitative Research''.<ref>Denzin, Norman K. and Yvonna S. Lincoln, Eds. (2005). ''The SAGE Handbook of Qualitative Research'', Thousand Oaks, CA, Sage Publications.</ref>\n\n=== Social exchange ===\n{{main|Social exchange theory}}\n[[Social exchange theory]] emphasizes the idea that social action is the result of ''personal choices'' made in order to maximize benefits and minimize costs. A key component of this theory is the postulation of the ''\"comparison level of alternatives\"'', which is the actor's sense of the best possible alternative (i.e. the choice with the highest net benefits or lowest net costs).\n\nTheories of social exchange share many essential features with classical economic theories like [[rational choice theory]]. However, social exchange theories differ from economic theories by making predictions about the relationships between persons, and not just the evaluation of goods. For example, social exchange theories  have been used to predict human behaviour in romantic relationships by taking into account each actor's subjective sense of costs (i.e., volatility, economic dependence), benefits (i.e., attraction, chemistry, attachment), and comparison level of alternatives (i.e., if any viable alternative mates are available).\n\n=== Theory of status characteristics and expectation states ===\n{{main|Expectation states theory}}\n[[Expectation states theory]] and its popular \"sub-theory\", status characteristics theory, proposes that individuals use available social information to form expectations for themselves and others. Group members use stereotypes about competence to attempt to determine who will be comparatively more skilled in any given task, indicating to whom the group should listen and accord [[Social status|status]]. Group members use known ability on the task at hand, membership in social categories (race, gender, age, education, etc.), and observed dominance behaviors (glares, rate of speech, interruptions, etc.) to determine everyone's relative ability and assign rank accordingly. While exhibiting dominant behavior or being of a certain race, for instance, has no direct connection to actual ability, implicit cultural beliefs about who is relatively more or less socially valued drive group members to \"act as if\" they believe some people have more useful contributions than others. As such, the theory has been used to explain the rise, persistence, and enactment of [[social status|status hierarchies]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ridgeway|first1=Cecilia L.|title=Why Status Matters for Inequality|journal=American Sociological Review|date=2014|volume=79|issue=1|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1177/0003122413515997}}</ref>\n\n=== Social structure and personality ===\nThis research perspective deals with relationships between large-scale social systems and individual behaviors and mental states including feelings, attitudes and values, and mental faculties.<ref>McLeod, Jane D. and Kathryn J. Lively (2003). \u201cSocial Structure and Personality.\u201d Pp. 77-102 in ''Handbook of Social Psychology'' edited by [[John DeLamater|J. DeLamater]]. New York: Kluwer/Plenum.</ref> Some researchers focus on issues of health and how social networks bring useful social support to the ill. Another line of research deals with how education, occupation, and other components of social class impact values. Some studies assess emotional variations, especially in happiness versus alienation and anger, among individuals in different structural positions.\n\n=== Social influence ===\n{{Main|Social influence}}\nSocial influence is a factor in every individual's life. Social influence takes place when one's thoughts, actions and feelings are affected by other people. It is a way of interaction that affects individual behavior and can occur within groups and between groups. It is a fundamental process that affects ways of socialization, conformity, leadership and social change.<ref>Smith, J. R., Louis, W. R., & Schultz, P. W. (2011). Introduction: Social influence in action. Group Processes & GP Intergroup Relations, 14(5), 599\u2013603.</ref>\n\n=== Dramaturgy ===\nAnother aspect of microsociology aims to focus on individual behavior in social settings. One specific researcher in the field, [[Erving Goffman]], claims that humans tend to believe that they are actors on a stage. He explains his theories in his book [[The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life]]. He argues that as a result, individuals will further proceed with their actions based on the response of that individual's 'audience' or in other words, the people to whom he is speaking. Much like a play, Goffman believes that rules of conversing and communication exist: to display confidence, display sincerity, and avoid infractions which are otherwise known as embarrassing situations. Breaches of such rules are what make social situations awkward.<ref>{{cite web|author=Your Name Here |url=http://www.soc.duke.edu/~jmoody77/TheoryNotes/Goffman.htm |title=Goffman: PSEL |publisher=Soc.duke.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Group processes ===\nFrom the sociological perspective, group processes scholars study how [[Power (social and political)|power]], [[Social status|status]], [[justice]], and [[legitimacy (political)|legitimacy]] impact the structure and interactions that take place within groups. Group processes scholars study how group size affects the type and quality of interactions that take place between group members, an area of study initiated by the work of the German social theorist, [[Georg Simmel]]. '''Dyads''' consist of two people and '''triads''' consist of three people, and the fundamental difference is that one person who leaves a dyad dissolves that group whereas the same is not true of a triad. The difference between these two types of groups also indicates the fundamental nature of group size, which is that every additional member of a group increases the group's stability but also decreases the possible amount of intimacy or interactions between any two members. [[Social group|Groups]] are also distinguished in terms of how and why the members know each other, and this stems from whether they are members of '''primary groups''' consisting of close friends and family held together by '''expressive ties'''; '''secondary groups''' consisting of coworkers, colleagues, classmates, etc. held together by '''instrumental ties'''; or '''reference groups''' consisting of people who do not necessarily know or interact with each other but who use each other for standards of comparison for appropriate behaviors. Group processes researchers also study interactions between groups, such as in the case of [[Muzafer Sherif]]'s [[Realistic conflict theory#Robbers cave study|Robbers Cave Experiment]].<ref>Rohall, D.E., Milkie, M.A., Lucas, J.W. 2014. Social Psychology: Sociological Perspectives. Pearson</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Behavioral economics]]\n* [[List of publications in psychology#Social psychology|Important publications in social psychology]]\n* [[List of social psychologists]]\n* [[Political psychology]]\n* [[Social psychology (psychology)|Social psychology (discipline within psychology)]]\n* [[Socialization]]\n* [[Sociobiology]]\n* [[Sociology]]\n* [[Socionics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikibooks|Social Psychology}}\n* [http://www.socialpsychology.org/ Social Psychology Network]\n* [http://www.spsp.org/ Society for Personality and Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.sesp.org/ Society of Experimental Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.apa.org/journals/psp.html Journal of Personality and Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.uiowa.edu/~grpproc/crisp/crisp.html Current Research in Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.trinity.edu/~mkearl/socpsy.html  Social Psychology - brief introduction]\n* [http://www.ship.edu/~cgboeree/socpsy.html Social Psychology basics]\n* [https://groups.yahoo.com/group/social_psychology/ Social Psychology forum]\n* [http://www.birchmore.org/html/scapegoating.html Scapegoating Processes in Groups]\n* [http://www.wilderdom.com/psychology/social/Introduction.html Introduction to Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.psychwiki.com/wiki/Main_Page PsychWiki]\n\n[[Category:Social philosophy]]\n[[Category:Interdisciplinary subfields of sociology]]\n[[Category:Behavioural sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the subfield of sociology|the subfield of psychology|social psychology}}\n{{Sociology}}\n\nIn [[sociology]], '''social psychology''', also known as '''sociological social psychology''' or '''microsociology''', is an area of sociology that focuses on [[social actions]] and on interrelations of [[personality]], [[Value (personal and cultural)|values]], and [[mind]] with [[social structure]] and [[culture]]. Some of the major topics in this field are [[social status]], structural \npower, [[Social change|sociocultural change]], [[social inequality]] and [[prejudice]], [[leadership]] and [[Group behaviour|intra-group behavior]], [[Social exchange theory|social exchange]], [[group conflict]], [[impression formation]] and [[Impression management|management]], [[Conversation analysis|conversation structures]], [[socialization]], [[social constructionism]], [[Norm (social)|social norms]] and [[Deviance (sociology)|deviance]], [[Identity (social science)|identity]] and [[role]]s, and [[emotional labor]]. The primary methods of data collection are [[Sampling (statistics)|sample surveys]], [[Observational study|field observations]], [[Vignette (psychology)|vignette studies]], [[field experiment]]s, and [[Design of experiments|controlled experiments]].\n\n== History ==\nSociological social psychology was born in 1902 with the landmark study by sociologist [[Charles Horton Cooley]], ''Human Nature and the Social Order'', which presented Cooley's concept of the [[looking glass self]]. The first textbook in social psychology by a sociologist appeared in 1908\u2014''Social Psychology'' by [[Edward Alsworth Ross]]. The area's main journal was founded as ''Sociometry'' by [[Jacob L. Moreno]] in 1937. The journal's name changed to ''Social Psychology'' in 1978, and to ''[[Social Psychology Quarterly]]'' in 1979.\n\nIn the 1920s [[W. I. Thomas]] contributed the notion of the [[definition of the situation]], with the [[Thomas theorem|proposition]] that became a basic tenet of sociology and sociological social psychology: \"If men define situations as real, they are real in their consequences.\"\n\nOne of the major currents of theory in this area sprang from work by philosopher and sociologist [[George Herbert Mead]] at the [[University of Chicago]] from 1894 forward.  Mead generally is credited as the founder of [[symbolic interactionism]]. Mead's colleague and disciple at Chicago, sociologist [[Herbert Blumer]], coined the name of the framework in 1937.\n\nSociologist [[Talcott Parsons]], at [[Harvard University]] from 1927 forward, developed a [[Cybernetics|cybernetic]] [[Action theory (sociology)|theory of action]] which was adapted to [[Communication in small groups|small group research]] by Parsons' student and colleague, [[Robert Freed Bales]], resulting in a body of observational studies of [[Social relation|social interaction]] in groups using Bales' behavior coding scheme, Interaction Process Analysis.<ref>Bales, Robert Freed (1950), ''Interaction Process Analysis'', New York: Addison-Wesley. Some studies using the method are included in Hare, A. Paul, Edgar F. Borgatta, & R. F. Bales (1955), ''Small Groups: Studies in Social Interaction'', New York: Alfred A. Knopf.</ref> During his 41-year tenure at Harvard, Bales mentored a distinguished group of sociological social psychologists concerned with [[Group dynamics|group processes]] and other topics in sociological social psychology.<ref>See the list of Bales' students at pages 332-3 of R. F. Bales (1999), ''Social Interaction Systems: Theory and Measurement'', New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction.</ref>\n\n==Major frameworks==\n\n=== Symbolic interactionism ===\n{{main|Symbolic interactionism}}\nContemporary symbolic interactionism originated out of ideas of George Herbert Mead and [[Max Weber]]. In this framework meanings are constructed during social interaction, and constructed meanings influence the process of social interaction. Many symbolic interactionists see the self as a core meaning constructed through social relations, and influencing social relations.\n\nThe structural school of symbolic interactionism uses shared social knowledge from a [[Macrosociology|macro-level]] [[culture]], [[natural language]], [[Institution|social institution]], or [[organization]] to explain relatively enduring patterns of social interaction and psychology at the [[Microsociology|micro-level]], typically investigating these matters with [[Quantitative research|quantitative methods]]. Identity theory,<ref>[[Sheldon Stryker|Stryker, Sheldon]], & Burke, Peter J. (2000). \"The past, present, and future of an identity theory\". ''Social Psychology Quarterly'' '''63''': 284\u2013297. Burke, P. J., and Jan E. Stets (2009). ''Identity Theory'', New York, Oxford University Press.</ref> [[affect control theory]],<ref>Heise, David R. (1979). ''Understanding Events: Affect and the Construction of Social Action'', New York: Cambridge University Press. MacKinnon, N. J. (1994). ''Symbolic Interactionism as Affect Control'', Albany, NY, State University of New York Press. Heise, D. R. (2007). ''Expressive Orider: Confirming Sentiments in Social Actions'', New York, Springer.</ref> and the Iowa School<ref>Miller, Dan E. (2011). \"Toward a Theory of Interaction: The Iowa School,\" ''Symbolic Interaction'' '''34''': 340-348.</ref> are major programs of research in this tradition. Identity Theory and Affect Control Theory both focus on how actions control mental states, thereby manifesting the underlying cybernetic nature of the approach, evident in Mead's writings<ref>MacKinnon, Neil J. (1994). ''Symbolic Interactionism as Affect Control'', Albany, NY, State University of New York Press. Pp. 3-5.</ref> Affect Control Theory provides a [[mathematical model]] of [[role theory]] and of [[labeling theory]].\n\nProcess symbolic interactionism stems from the [[Chicago school (sociology)|Chicago School]] and considers the meanings underlying social interactions to be situated, creative, fluid, and often contested. Researchers in this tradition frequently use [[qualitative research|qualitative]] and [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] methods. A journal, ''Symbolic Interaction'', was founded in 1977 by the Society for the Study of Symbolic Interaction as a central outlet for the empirical research and [[Conceptual system|conceptual studies]] produced by scholars in this area.\n\n[[Postmodernism|Postmodern]] symbolic interactionists understand the notions of self and identity to be increasingly fragmented and illusory, and consider attempts at theorizing to be [[meta-narrative]]s with no more authority than other conversations. The approach is presented in detail by ''The SAGE Handbook of Qualitative Research''.<ref>Denzin, Norman K. and Yvonna S. Lincoln, Eds. (2005). ''The SAGE Handbook of Qualitative Research'', Thousand Oaks, CA, Sage Publications.</ref>\n\n=== Social exchange ===\n{{main|Social exchange theory}}\n[[Social exchange theory]] emphasizes the idea that social action is the result of ''personal choices'' made in order to maximize benefits and minimize costs. A key component of this theory is the postulation of the ''\"comparison level of alternatives\"'', which is the actor's sense of the best possible alternative (i.e. the choice with the highest net benefits or lowest net costs).\n\nTheories of social exchange share many essential features with classical economic theories like [[rational choice theory]]. However, social exchange theories differ from economic theories by making predictions about the relationships between persons, and not just the evaluation of goods. For example, social exchange theories  have been used to predict human behaviour in romantic relationships by taking into account each actor's subjective sense of costs (i.e., volatility, economic dependence), benefits (i.e., attraction, chemistry, attachment), and comparison level of alternatives (i.e., if any viable alternative mates are available).\n\n=== Theory of status characteristics and expectation states ===\n{{main|Expectation states theory}}\n[[Expectation states theory]] and its popular \"sub-theory\", status characteristics theory, proposes that individuals use available social information to form expectations for themselves and others. Group members use stereotypes about competence to attempt to determine who will be comparatively more skilled in any given task, indicating to whom the group should listen and accord [[Social status|status]]. Group members use known ability on the task at hand, membership in social categories (race, gender, age, education, etc.), and observed dominance behaviors (glares, rate of speech, interruptions, etc.) to determine everyone's relative ability and assign rank accordingly. While exhibiting dominant behavior or being of a certain race, for instance, has no direct connection to actual ability, implicit cultural beliefs about who is relatively more or less socially valued drive group members to \"act as if\" they believe some people have more useful contributions than others. As such, the theory has been used to explain the rise, persistence, and enactment of [[social status|status hierarchies]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ridgeway|first1=Cecilia L.|title=Why Status Matters for Inequality|journal=American Sociological Review|date=2014|volume=79|issue=1|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1177/0003122413515997}}</ref>\n\n=== Social structure and personality ===\nThis research perspective deals with relationships between large-scale social systems and individual behaviors and mental states including feelings, attitudes and values, and mental faculties.<ref>McLeod, Jane D. and Kathryn J. Lively (2003). \u201cSocial Structure and Personality.\u201d Pp. 77-102 in ''Handbook of Social Psychology'' edited by [[John DeLamater|J. DeLamater]]. New York: Kluwer/Plenum.</ref> Some researchers focus on issues of health and how social networks bring useful social support to the ill. Another line of research deals with how education, occupation, and other components of social class impact values. Some studies assess emotional variations, especially in happiness versus alienation and anger, among individuals in different structural positions.\n\n=== Social influence ===\n{{Main|Social influence}}\nSocial influence is a factor in every individual's life. Social influence takes place when one's thoughts, actions and feelings are affected by other people. It is a way of interaction that affects individual behavior and can occur within groups and between groups. It is a fundamental process that affects ways of socialization, conformity, leadership and social change.<ref>Smith, J. R., Louis, W. R., & Schultz, P. W. (2011). Introduction: Social influence in action. Group Processes & GP Intergroup Relations, 14(5), 599\u2013603.</ref>\n\n=== Dramaturgy ===\nAnother aspect of microsociology aims to focus on individual behavior in social settings. One specific researcher in the field, [[Erving Goffman]], claims that humans tend to believe that they are actors on a stage. He explains his theories in his book [[The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life]]. He argues that as a result, individuals will further proceed with their actions based on the response of that individual's 'audience' or in other words, the people to whom he is speaking. Much like a play, Goffman believes that rules of conversing and communication exist: to display confidence, display sincerity, and avoid infractions which are otherwise known as embarrassing situations. Breaches of such rules are what make social situations awkward.<ref>{{cite web|author=Your Name Here |url=http://www.soc.duke.edu/~jmoody77/TheoryNotes/Goffman.htm |title=Goffman: PSEL |publisher=Soc.duke.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Group processes ===\nFrom the sociological perspective, group processes scholars study how [[Power (social and political)|power]], [[Social status|status]], [[justice]], and [[legitimacy (political)|legitimacy]] impact the structure and interactions that take place within groups. Group processes scholars study how group size affects the type and quality of interactions that take place between group members, an area of study initiated by the work of the German social theorist, [[Georg Simmel]]. '''Dyads''' consist of two people and '''triads''' consist of three people, and the fundamental difference is that one person who leaves a dyad dissolves that group whereas the same is not true of a triad. The difference between these two types of groups also indicates the fundamental nature of group size, which is that every additional member of a group increases the group's stability but also decreases the possible amount of intimacy or interactions between any two members. [[Social group|Groups]] are also distinguished in terms of how and why the members know each other, and this stems from whether they are members of '''primary groups''' consisting of close friends and family held together by '''expressive ties'''; '''secondary groups''' consisting of coworkers, colleagues, classmates, etc. held together by '''instrumental ties'''; or '''reference groups''' consisting of people who do not necessarily know or interact with each other but who use each other for standards of comparison for appropriate behaviors. Group processes researchers also study interactions between groups, such as in the case of [[Muzafer Sherif]]'s [[Realistic conflict theory#Robbers cave study|Robbers Cave Experiment]].<ref>Rohall, D.E., Milkie, M.A., Lucas, J.W. 2014. Social Psychology: Sociological Perspectives. Pearson</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Behavioral economics]]\n* [[List of publications in psychology#Social psychology|Important publications in social psychology]]\n* [[List of social psychologists]]\n* [[Political psychology]]\n* [[Social psychology (psychology)|Social psychology (discipline within psychology)]]\n* [[Socialization]]\n* [[Sociobiology]]\n* [[Sociology]]\n* [[Socionics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikibooks|Social Psychology}}\n* [http://www.socialpsychology.org/ Social Psychology Network]\n* [http://www.spsp.org/ Society for Personality and Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.sesp.org/ Society of Experimental Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.apa.org/journals/psp.html Journal of Personality and Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.uiowa.edu/~grpproc/crisp/crisp.html Current Research in Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.trinity.edu/~mkearl/socpsy.html  Social Psychology - brief introduction]\n* [http://www.ship.edu/~cgboeree/socpsy.html Social Psychology basics]\n* [https://groups.yahoo.com/group/social_psychology/ Social Psychology forum]\n* [http://www.birchmore.org/html/scapegoating.html Scapegoating Processes in Groups]\n* [http://www.wilderdom.com/psychology/social/Introduction.html Introduction to Social Psychology]\n* [http://www.psychwiki.com/wiki/Main_Page PsychWiki]\n\n[[Category:Social philosophy]]\n[[Category:Interdisciplinary subfields of sociology]]\n[[Category:Behavioural sciences]]\n", "name_user": "Guavabutter", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_psychology_(sociology)"}
{"title_page": "BYJU'S", "text_new": "{{short description|India-based educational technology and online tutoring firm}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Think and Learn Private Ltd.\n| logo = BYJU'S logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Edtech]], [[distance education]], [[m-learning]]\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2011}}<ref name=entrep>{{cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/310403|title=Decoding Byju's Journey From Start-up to Unicorn|first=Sandeep|last=Soni|date=14 March 2018|work=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur India]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180324083500/https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/310403|archivedate=24 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n| founder =Byju Raveedran\n\n{{small|(Founder, [[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}<ref name=bloomberg /><ref name=et2018a />\n| defunct = \n| hq_location_city = [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], [[Karnataka]]<ref name=entrep />\n| hq_location_country = [[India]]\n| area_served = [[Multinational]]\n| key_people = \n| products = BYJU\u2019S - The Learning App\n| owner = \n| num_employees = 3200\n| num_employees_year = 2019<ref name=vbeat2019>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/21/why-indias-ed-tech-firm-byjus-paid-120-million-for-kids-ar-game-maker-osmo/|title=Why India's ed-tech firm Byju's paid $120 million for kids AR game maker Osmo|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|website=[[VentureBeat]]|date=21 January 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502074933/https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/21/why-indias-ed-tech-firm-byjus-paid-120-million-for-kids-ar-game-maker-osmo/|archivedate=2 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue = {{increase}} {{INRConvert|5200|m|year=2018|to=USD EUR}} (2018)<ref name=qz2018>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1248788/byjus-indias-newest-unicorn-is-going-global-with-its-exam-prep-business/|title=After turning exam prep into a booming business, India's newest unicorn is going global|last=U N|first=Sushma|date=16 April 2018|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz India]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416082817/https://qz.com/1248788/byjus-indias-newest-unicorn-is-going-global-with-its-exam-prep-business/|archivedate=16 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n| equity = $5.4 billion\n| equity_year = 2019<ref name=et2019>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/byjus-value-at-5-4bn-via-new-25m-round/articleshow/68517172.cms|title=Byju's value at $5.4bn via new $25m round|first1=Digbijay|last1=Mishra|first2=Madhav|last2=Chanchani|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=22 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404205614/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/byjus-value-at-5-4bn-via-new-25m-round/articleshow/68517172.cms|archivedate=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n| subsid = [[TutorVista]], [[Osmo (game system)|Osmo]]\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|https://byjus.com}}\n}}\n'\n'''BYJU\u2019S - The Learning App''' is the common brand name for '''Think and Learn Private Ltd.,''' a [[India]]n [[Educational technology]] (edtech) and online tutoring firm founded in 2011 by Byju Ravindran at [[Bengaluru]] ([[India]]).<ref name=bloomberg>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-20/zuckerberg-or-gates-billionaires-try-opposites-paths-for-online-education-in-india|title=Zuckerberg or Gates? Billionaires Try Opposite Paths for Online Education in India|first=Saritha|last=Rai|date=21 June 2017|publisher=[[Bloomberg Technology]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180324072640/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-20/zuckerberg-or-gates-billionaires-try-opposites-paths-for-online-education-in-india|archivedate=24 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=fexpress>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/opinion/byjus-on-way-to-turn-indias-first-education-based-unicorn-ceo-byju-raveendran-on-how-he-turned-it-into-mammoth-online-venture/708927/|title=Byju's on way to turn India's first education based unicorn, CEO [Byju Raveendran] on how he turned it into mammoth online venture|first= Darlington|last=Jose Hector|date=9 June 2017|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324073529/http://www.financialexpress.com/opinion/byjus-on-way-to-turn-indias-first-education-based-unicorn-ceo-byju-raveendran-on-how-he-turned-it-into-mammoth-online-venture/708927/|archivedate=24 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\nIn March 2019, it was the world\u2019s most valued [[edtech]] company at $5.4 billion (Rs 37,000 [[crore]]). [[Shah Rukh Khan]] is the brand ambassador for '''BYJU'S'''. In July 2019 BYJU'S assigned Indian cricket team jersey rights.\n\n== Products and Services ==\nBYJU\u2019S runs on a [[freemium]] model.<ref name=tech2016>{{cite web|url= http://techcircle.vccircle.com/2016/03/22/ed-tech-startup-byjus-raises-75m-from-sequoia-sofina/|title=Ed-tech startup Byju's raises $75M from Sequoia, Sofina|first=Priya|last=Prasad|date=22 March 2016|website=[[VCCircle]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331161943/http://techcircle.vccircle.com/2016/03/22/ed-tech-startup-byjus-raises-75m-from-sequoia-sofina/|archivedate=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> Free access to content is limited to 15 days after the registration.<ref name=tech2016 /><ref name=manorama>{{cite web|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/business/news/byju-raveendran-50-million-investments-facebook-zuckerberg.html|title=Byju Raveendran: From a Malayalam school to an app with Zuckerberg funding|first=Ajish|last=George|date=12 September 2016|newspaper=[[Malayala Manorama]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331163007/https://english.manoramaonline.com/business/news/byju-raveendran-50-million-investments-facebook-zuckerberg.html|archivedate=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nTheir main product is a [[mobile app]] named ''BYJU'S-The Learning App'' launched in August 2015.<ref name=\"rediff_201610\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/business/interview/two-lakh-to-330-crore-the-byjus-classes-success-story/20161007.htm|title=2 lakh to 3300 crore: The BYJU's Classes success story|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|website=[[Rediff.com]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802204802/http://www.rediff.com/business/interview/two-lakh-to-330-crore-the-byjus-classes-success-story/20161007.htm|archivedate=2 August 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> It provides educational content mainly to school students from class 1 to 12 (primary to [[higher secondary]] level education).<ref name=et2018a /> The company trains students for examinations in [[India]] such as [[IIT-JEE]], [[National Eligibility and Entrance Test|NEET]], [[Common Admission Test|CAT]], [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] as well as for international examinations such as [[GRE]] and [[GMAT]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/byjus-ceo-targets-entry-into-unicorn-club-aims-to-turn-profitable-in-fy18-2286985.html|title=Byjus' CEO targets entry into unicorn club; aims to turn profitable in FY18|first=Durba|last=Ghosh|date=24 May 2017|website=[[Moneycontrol.com]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331144119/https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/byjus-ceo-targets-entry-into-unicorn-club-aims-to-turn-profitable-in-fy18-2286985.html|archivedate=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe main focus is on [[mathematics]] and [[science]], where concepts are explained using 12-20 minute [[Computer animation|digital animation]]videos.<ref name=\"ecotimes_201606\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/wealth/earn/why-byju-raveendrans-firm-is-leading-in-the-educational-technology-space/articleshow/52700525.cms|title=Why Byju Raveendran's firm is leading in the educational technology space|last=Dwivedi|first=Vinay|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=13 June 2016|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"qz_201607\">{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/740893/an-engineer-has-built-indias-largest-education-technology-startup-by-helping-students-get-into-the-iims/|title=India's largest edu-tech startup was built by an engineer who aced CAT for fun\u2014twice|last=Karnik|first=Madhura|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|date=27 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801073300/https://qz.com/740893/an-engineer-has-built-indias-largest-education-technology-startup-by-helping-students-get-into-the-iims/|archivedate=1 August 2016|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes_201609\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/hidden-gems-2016/how-byjus-fills-the-biggest-gap-in-indian-education/44247/1|title=How Byju's fills the biggest gap in Indian education|last=Shree|first=Shilpa|website=[[Forbes India]]|language=en-US|date=9 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731184429/http://www.forbesindia.com/article/hidden-gems-2016/how-byjus-fills-the-biggest-gap-in-indian-education/44247/1|archivedate=31 July 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> BYJU'S reports to have 33 million users overall, 2.2 million annual paid subscribers and an annual retention rate of about 85%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessworld.in/article/Byju-s-Group-The-World-Is-His-Classroom/29-04-2019-169817/|title=Byju's Group: The World Is His Classroom|first=Suman|last=K Jha|work=[[Businessworld]]|date=29 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502150713/http://www.businessworld.in/article/Byju-s-Group-The-World-Is-His-Classroom/29-04-2019-169817/|archivedate=2 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/sindhujabalaji/2018/03/11/how-are-indias-biggest-edtech-startups-winning-students-by-treating-it-like-a-game/|title=How Are India's Biggest EdTech Startups Winning Students? By Treating It Like A Game|first=Sindhuja|last=Balaji|date=11 March 2018|work=[[Forbes India]]|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> The app purports to tailor the content provided to the individual student\u2019s learning pace and style.<ref name=pcmag>{{cite web|url=http://in.pcmag.com/edtech/117879/feature/how-byjus-built-indias-most-popular-learning-app|title=How BYJU'S built India's most popular learning app|first=Jibu|last=Elias|date=6 December 2017|work=[[PC Magazine|PC Magazine India]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718180351/http://in.pcmag.com/edtech/117879/feature/how-byjus-built-indias-most-popular-learning-app|archivedate=18 July 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> The average student spends 53 minutes daily using BYJU'S.<ref name=fortuneindia2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.fortuneindia.com/enterprise/byjus-raises-540-mln-from-naspers-cppib/102785|title=Byju's raises $540 mln from Naspers, CPPIB|first=Deepti|last=Chaudhary|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] India|date=17 December 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502085421/https://www.fortuneindia.com/enterprise/byjus-raises-540-mln-from-naspers-cppib/102785|archivedate=2 May 2019|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company announced that it will launch its app in regional Indian languages in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bestmediainfo.com/2017/11/byju-s-looking-at-regional-languages-and-international-markets-for-growth/|title=Byju's looking at regional languages and international markets for growth|first=Roshni|last=Nair|date=22 November 2017|website=bestmediainfo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331155917/http://bestmediainfo.com/2017/11/byju-s-looking-at-regional-languages-and-international-markets-for-growth/|archivedate=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=et2018a /> It also plans to launch an international version of the app for English-speaking students in other countries in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://techcircle.vccircle.com/2018/03/09/why-ed-tech-startup-byju-s-will-build-not-buy-for-its-global-expansion|title= Why ed-tech startup Byju's will build, not buy, for its global expansion|first1=Anand|last1=J.|first2=Dearton Thomas|last2=Hector|date=9 March 2018|website=[[VCCircle]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190502090122/https://www.techcircle.in/2018/03/09/why-ed-tech-startup-byju-s-will-build-not-buy-for-its-global-expansion|archivedate=2 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/12/17/byjus-raises-540-million/|title=Byju's targets global expansion for its digital education service after raising $540M|first=Jon|last=Russell|website=[[TechCrunch]]|date=17 December 2018|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBYJU\u2019S app was developed by Think and Learn Pvt Ltd, established by [[Byju Raveendran]] in 2011.<ref name=bloomberg /><ref name=entrep /> Raveendran, who was trained as an engineer, started coaching students to pass mathematics exams in 2006.<ref name=bloomberg /> In 2011 he founded an educational company with the help of his students offering online video-based learning programs for the [[K-12]] segment as well as competition exams.<ref name=8students>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/how-8-students-helped-byju-raveendran-build-his-multi-crore-edtech-business/articleshow/59274288.cms|title=How 8 students helped Byju Raveendran build his multi-crore edtech business|author=J Vignesh|date=23 June 2017|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412072941/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/how-8-students-helped-byju-raveendran-build-his-multi-crore-edtech-business/articleshow/59274288.cms|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/overseas-expansion-acquisition-on-byju-raveendrans-mind/articleshow/53392426.cms|title=Overseas expansion, acquisition on Byju Raveendran's mind|author=Anu Thomas|date= 28 July 2016|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413112147/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/overseas-expansion-acquisition-on-byju-raveendrans-mind/articleshow/53392426.cms|archivedate=13 April 2018|accessdate= 4 May 2019}}</ref> In 2012 Think and Learn entered both Deloitte Technology Fast50 India and [[Deloitte Technology Fast 500|Deloitte Technology Fast 500 Asia Pacific]] ratings and has been present there ever since.<ref name=entrep /><ref name=del>{{cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/in/Documents/technology-media-telecommunications/in-tmt-tech-fast-50-winners-report-17-noexp.pdf|title=Deloitte Technology Fast50 India 2017 Ranking|year=2017|publisher=[[Deloitte]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412073224/https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/in/Documents/technology-media-telecommunications/in-tmt-tech-fast-50-winners-report-17-noexp.pdf|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, after 4 years of developments, the firm launched BYJU\u2019S The Learning App.<ref name=financial2018>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/education-2/reinventing-the-classroom-says-byju-raveendran-of-byjus-the-learning-app/755401/|title=Reinventing the classroom, says Byju Raveendran of Byju's: The Learning App|author=Gaurab Dasgupta|date=25 August 2017|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412074915/http://www.financialexpress.com/education-2/reinventing-the-classroom-says-byju-raveendran-of-byjus-the-learning-app/755401/|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=8students /> The app was downloaded by more than 2 million students within the first 3 months since its launch.<ref name=entrep /> In December 2016, the app was among \"Best Self Improvement\" apps at Google Play India rating.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://naradanews.com/2016/12/best-of-2016-apps-from-google-play/|title=Best of 2016 apps from Google Play|date=3 December 2016|website= naradanews.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412075551/http://naradanews.com/2016/12/best-of-2016-apps-from-google-play/|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Think and Learn launched BYJU\u2019S Math App for kids and BYJU\u2019S Parent Connect app to help parents track their child\u2019s learning course.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/Byjus-new-gamified-app-wantsto-make-studying-Maths-real-fun-for-students/articleshow/57166026.cms|title=Byju's new gamified app wants to make studying Maths real fun for students|first=Tanya|last=Dubey|date=15 February 2017|work=[[Business Insider| Business Insider India]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412075729/https://www.businessinsider.in/Byjus-new-gamified-app-wantsto-make-studying-Maths-real-fun-for-students/articleshow/57166026.cms|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/education/parent-connect-app-will-track-the-childs-learning-journey-says-byjus-ceo/article9715336.ece|title= Parent connect app will track the child's learning journey, says Byju's CEO|author=Venkatesh Ganesh|publisher=[[Business Line]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412075855/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/education/parent-connect-app-will-track-the-childs-learning-journey-says-byjus-ceo/article9715336.ece|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> BYJU\u2019S app also became a [[Case method|business case]] at [[Harvard Business School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/byjus-now-a-part-of-harvard-business-school-case-study/articleshow/58516160.cms|title=Byju's now a part of Harvard Business School case study|author=J Vignesh|date=4 May 2017|publisher=[[The Economic Times]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412080013/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/byjus-now-a-part-of-harvard-business-school-case-study/articleshow/58516160.cms|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://mashable.com/2017/05/05/zuckerberg-backed-edutech-startup-harvard-case-study/|title= Mark Zuckerberg-backed edutech startup is now a Harvard case study|first=Sonini|last=Mitter|date=5 May 2017|website=[[Mashable]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082351/https://mashable.com/2017/05/05/zuckerberg-backed-edutech-startup-harvard-case-study/#zHm0NI_t0iq2|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> By 2018, it had 15 million users and 900,000 paid users.<ref name=et2018a>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/byjus-targets-rs-1300-crore-revenue-next-year/articleshow/63397720.cms|title=Byju's targets Rs 1300 crore revenue next year|first=Krishna|last=Kumar|date=21 March 2018|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180324080218/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/byjus-targets-rs-1300-crore-revenue-next-year/articleshow/63397720.cms|archivedate=24 March 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=economist>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21737096-byjus-has-900000-paid-users-and-investment-sequoia-capital-and-chinas-tencent-indian|title=Indian teaching startups make work for idle thumbs|date=17 February 2018|website=[[The Economist]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217112341/https://www.economist.com/news/business/21737096-byjus-has-900000-paid-users-and-investment-sequoia-capital-and-chinas-tencent-indian|archivedate= 17 February 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Acquisitions ==\nIn July 2017, Think and Learn acquired [[TutorVista]] (including Edurite) from [[Pearson plc|Pearson]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.livemint.com/Companies/VtOJY1jBZSOrtBvyLzsrhI/Byjus-acquires-TutorVista-Eduvista-in-push-for-global-expa.html|title=Byju's buys Pearson's TutorVista, Edurite in push for global expansion|author=Sayan Chakraborty|date=4 July 2017|newspaper=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082807/https://www.livemint.com/Companies/VtOJY1jBZSOrtBvyLzsrhI/Byjus-acquires-TutorVista-Eduvista-in-push-for-global-expa.html|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/byjus-acquires-tutorvista-and-edurite/articleshow/59427281.cms|title= Byju's acquires TutorVista, Edurite from Pearson|author=J Vignesh|date=3 July 2017|publisher=[[The Economic Times]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082950/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/byjus-acquires-tutorvista-and-edurite/articleshow/59427281.cms|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes_201707\">{{cite news|last=Dhamija|first=Anshul|title=Byju's acquires TutorVista and Edurite from Pearson|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/special/byjus-acquires-tutorvista-and-edurite-from-pearson/47449/1|work=[[Forbes India]]|date=3 July 2017|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, BYJU\u2019S acquired a [[United States|US]]-based [[Osmo (game system)|Osmo]], a maker of educational games for children aged 3\u20138 years for $120 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/80Le6wvAY3xi3jFSs5FJLI/Byjus-acquires-USbased-Osmo-for-120-million.html|title=Byju's acquires US-based Osmo for $120 million|first=Deepti|last=Govind|website=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=19 January 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205042058/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/80Le6wvAY3xi3jFSs5FJLI/Byjus-acquires-USbased-Osmo-for-120-million.html|archivedate=5 February 2019|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Funding and financials ==\nBYJU\u2019S received [[Seed money|seed funding]] from  Aarin Capital in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/an-entrepreneur-by-heart-fortis-manipal-deal-makes-ranjan-pai-the-new-king-of-indias-healthcare-industry-2538335.html|title=An entrepreneur at heart, Ranjan Pai is the new king of India's healthcare industry|author=Prince Mathews Thomas|date=29 March 2018|website=[[Moneycontrol.com]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412084323/https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/an-entrepreneur-by-heart-fortis-manipal-deal-makes-ranjan-pai-the-new-king-of-indias-healthcare-industry-2538335.html|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, BYJU\u2019S has secured nearly $785 million in funding from investors, including [[Sequoia Capital|Sequoia Capital India]], [[Chan Zuckerberg Initiative]] (CZI), [[Tencent]], [[Sofina]], [[Lightspeed Venture Partners]], [[Brussels]]-based family office Verlinvest, development finance institution [[International Finance Corporation|IFC]], [[Naspers|Napsters Ventures]], [[CPP Investment Board|CPPIB]] and [[General Atlantic]].<ref name=economist /><ref name=et2018b>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/edutech-startup-byjus-quietly-turns-a-unicorn-company/articleshow/63293773.cms|title=Here's how edutech startup Byju's quietly turned into a unicorn company|first1=J|last1=Vignesh|first2=Madhav|last2=Chanchani|date=14 March 2018|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180324081409/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/edutech-startup-byjus-quietly-turns-a-unicorn-company/articleshow/63293773.cms|archivedate=24 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vccircle.com/cppib-general-atlantic-others-back-byju-s-in-mega-funding-round/|title=CPPIB, General Atlantic & others back Byju's in Naspers-led mega funding round|first=Vijayakumar|last=Pitchiah|website=[[VCCircle]]|date=11 December 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411014655/https://www.vccircle.com/cppib-general-atlantic-others-back-byju-s-in-mega-funding-round/|archivedate=11 April 2019|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> BYJU\u2019S was the first company in [[Asia]] to receive an investment from Chan-Zuckerberg Initiative (co-funded by [[Facebook]] founder [[Mark Zuckerberg]] and [[Priscilla Chan (philanthropist)|Priscilla Chan]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/sep/21/mark-zuckerberg-priscilla-chan-end-disease|title=Priscilla Chan and Mark Zuckerberg aim to 'cure, prevent and manage' all disease|author=Olivia Solon|date=22 September 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412091640/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/sep/21/mark-zuckerberg-priscilla-chan-end-disease|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/byjus-raises-50m-co-led-by-chan-zuckerberg-initiative-1473357848|title=Byju's Raises $50M Co-led by Chan Zuckerberg Initiative|date=8 September 2016|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]| accessdate=4 May 2019}}{{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.cnbc.com/2016/12/07/how-start-up-byjus-shrugged-off-a-slowdown-and-snagged-cash-from-mark-zuckerberg.html|title= How this start-up shrugged off a slowdown and snagged cash from Mark Zuckerberg|author=Gauri Bhatia|date=8 December 2016|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412092620/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/12/07/how-start-up-byjus-shrugged-off-a-slowdown-and-snagged-cash-from-mark-zuckerberg.html|archivedate=12 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs per the company filings with the [[Ministry of Corporate Affairs]], BYJU\u2019S became a [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] and is valued at {{USD}}1 billion (INR 6,505 Crore) as of March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inc42.com/buzz/the-rise-of-indias-billion-dollar-club-edtech-startup-byjus-turns-unicorn/|title=The Rise Of India's Billion-Dollar Club: Edtech Startup BYJU'S Turns Unicorn|last=Anupam|first=Suprita|date=14 March 2018|website=inc42.com|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=et2018b />\n\nBYJU'S operates roughly on a premium business model where a paid subscription is required for most of the content.<ref name=\"ecotimes_201606\"/> In 2017, BYJU\u2019s generated revenues of about 260 crore (US $40 million or \u20ac33 million) and doubled it 2018 financial year, earning 520 crore.<ref name=fexpress /><ref name=qz2018 /> BYJU\u2019S has targeted a revenue of 1400 crores for 2019 financial year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/byjus-ups-revenue-to-rs-490-cr-in-fy-18-drops-losses-by-half/articleshow/67474606.cms|title=Byju's ups revenue to Rs 490 cr in FY 18, drops losses by half|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=10 January 2019|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award or recognition\n! Type of award\n! Result/ranking\n|-\n|  2017\n| Express IT Awards\n| Personal\n| {{won}}<ref name=finex2017>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/express-it-awards-byju-raveendran-a-teacher-who-is-the-pupils-pet/955037/|title=Express IT Awards: Byju Raveendran, a teacher who is the pupils' pet|date=4 December 2017|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180401100442/http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/express-it-awards-byju-raveendran-a-teacher-who-is-the-pupils-pet/955037/|archivedate=1 April 2018|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| Deloitte Technology Fast 500 Asia Pacific\n| Company\n| 126<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/global/Documents/Technology-Media-Telecommunications/2017-tech-fast500-apac-ranking-