{"title_page": "Steve McFadden", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Steve McFadden\n| image              = Steve McFadden.jpg\n| caption            = McFadden at the 2011 [[The British Soap Awards|British Soap Awards]]\n| birth_name         = Steve Robert Reid\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1959|3|20|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve McFadden|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/celebrities/steve-mcfadden/#~oHzc5qVHJ183Ox|publisher=DigitalSpy|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Maida Vale]], [[London]], England\n| occupation         = [[Actor]]\n| years active       = 1988\u2013present\n| known_for          = ''[[The Bill]]'' (1989)'' <br> [[EastEnders]]'' (1990\u20132003, 2005\u2013)\n| children           = 5\n}}\n'''Steve Robert McFadden''' (n\u00e9 '''Reid''', born 20 March 1959) is an English actor. He is known for his role as [[Phil Mitchell]] in the [[BBC One|BBC]] soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]'', which he has played since 1990. He was also the presenter of fighting series ''[[Britain's Hardest]]''.\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from RADA in 1987,<ref>{{cite web|title=Eastenders actor Steve McFadden hopes to show a 'softer' side of Phil Mitchell|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/entertainment/eastenders_actor_steve_mcfadden_hopes_to_show_a_softer_side_of_phil_mitchell_1_3085685|publisher=Ham&High News|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref> he made his acting debut playing a small role in the 1988 television film ''[[The Firm (1988 film)|The Firm]]''. That same year, he had an uncredited brief appearance in the film ''[[Buster (film)|Buster]]'' as a gang member. This was followed by appearances in the television series ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' and ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]''.\n\nMcFadden then rose to fame for portraying the role of [[Phil Mitchell]] in the [[BBC One|BBC]] soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]''. He joined ''EastEnders'' at the beginning of 1990, at the same time as [[Ross Kemp]], who played Phil's younger brother [[Grant Mitchell (EastEnders)|Grant Mitchell]]. During that time, his character was involved in numerous storylines, such as [[Sharongate]] (where it was revealed that he had an affair with his brother's wife [[Sharon Watts|Sharon]]) in 1994, and the [[Who Shot Phil?]] storyline in March 2001; where his character was shot and wounded by a mystery attacker. The identity of the attacker was revealed weeks later as Phil's girlfriend [[Lisa Fowler|Lisa]], played by [[Lucy Benjamin]].\n\nMcFadden then made an appearance in the film ''[[Kevin & Perry Go Large]]'' in 2000,<ref name=\"Kevin and Perry\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4403694.stm | title=Profiles: EastEnders Kemp and McFadden | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=3 November 2005 | accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> and starred in an episode of the BBC anthology series ''[[Murder in Mind (TV series)|Murder in Mind]]'' in 2001. He left ''EastEnders'' in late 2003 for a one-year break to concentrate on [[pantomimes]]. His character was written out of the series after being framed for an armed robbery by [[Den Watts]] (played by [[Leslie Grantham]]), and going on the run after breaking out of prison. During his break from ''EastEnders'', he presented the reality fighting series ''Britain's Hardest'' which was an underground competition broadcast on [[Sky One]]. He returned to ''EastEnders'' for two episodes in April 2005. In the story, Phil returned to Walford in need of financial help, only to be arrested and returned to prison. In October 2005, he returned on a permanent basis, after his character was cleared of armed robbery.\n\nIn 2007, he appeared in the film ''[[Provoked (film)|Provoked]]''. He has also appeared as Captain Hook in a pantomime production of ''[[Peter Pan (1954 musical)|Peter Pan]]'' from 2010 to 2011 at [[The Swan (theatre)|The Swan]]. From 2012 to 2013, he appeared in ''Aladdin'', playing Abanazar, at the [[Orchard Theatre, Dartford|Orchard Theatre]].\n\nHe was placed in a strip in the comic Viz where, for no apparent reason, he attended a private school for girls where all his classmates were eleven or twelve years old. The wealthy students bullied him for being poor and having a shabby-looking pony, until it was discovered at the end of the story that he was really a princess!\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"20\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"300\"| Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"300\"| Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"10\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2001 || [[National Television Awards]] || Most Popular Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n|[[British Soap Awards]] || Villain of the Year || {{Won}} \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Inside Soap Awards]] || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Best Bad Boy || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Most Dramatic Storyline ([[Who Shot Phil?]]) || {{Won}}\n|- \n| rowspan=\"3\"|2002 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|British Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Villain of the Year || {{Nom}} \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2003 \n| Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Villain of the Year || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Inside Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|2006\n|rowspan=\"3\"| British Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Villain of the Year || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Spectacular Scene of the Year (skip crashes onto Phil Mitchell's car) || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Inside Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Family ([[Mitchell family]]) || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2007 || [[TV Choice|TVChoice Awards]] || Best Soap Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| [[TV Now Awards]] || Male Soap Star || {{Won}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2008 || British Soap Awards || Spectacular Scene of the Year (Phil Mitchell's car rolling into a lake) || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| [[Digital Spy Soap Awards]] || Best Single Episode (Phil Mitchell and [[Stella Crawford]]'s wedding) || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2009 || British Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2010 \n| rowspan=\"2\"|TV Now Awards || Favourite Male Soap Star || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Favourite Soap Family (Mitchell family) || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2012 || [[All About Soap|All About Soap Awards]] || Best Mystery (Who's Stalking Phil Mitchell?) || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2016 \n| British Soap Awards || Outstanding Achievement Award || {{Won}}\n|-\n| British Soap Awards || Best Male Dramatic Performance || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Inside Soap Awards || Best Soap Actor || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2017\n| British Soap Awards || Best Male Dramatic Performance || {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcFadden has five children. His son Matt McFadden's mother is Sue Marshall, and Angela Bostock is the mother of his daughters Teona and Mollie Jane. Rachel Sidwell gave birth to his daughter Amelie Tinkerbell on 29 June 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/a162792/enders-star-mcfadden-welcomes-baby-girl.html|title='Enders star McFadden welcomes baby girl|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|first=Lara|last=Martin|date=30 June 2009|accessdate=7 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.stv.tv/tv/111723-steve-mcfadden-happier-than-ever/|title=Steve McFadden 'happier than ever'|publisher=MyParkMag|date=26 July 2009|accessdate=29 July 2009}}{{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref> At the time she was his partner, but the couple split two months later.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/200909152023/steve-mcfadden/dr-rachel-sidwell/split|title=Mum of 'EastEnders' actor Steve's new baby calls time on their relationship|date=15 September 2009|accessdate=20 April 2020|work=[[Hello Magazine]]}}</ref> A fifth child, a daughter named Frankie, was born to his girlfriend Karen Cairns in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-steve-mcfadden-dad-fifth-8117039|title=EastEnders' Steve McFadden is 'dad for fifth time with fourth woman, as he welcomes baby daughter' |last=Corner|first=Natalie|date=5 June 2016|work=[[The Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is an active sailor,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yachtingmonthly.com/news/529359/tv-star-s-loathing-for-gin-palaces | title=TV star's loathing for gin palaces | publisher=Yachting Monthly | accessdate=1 January 2013 | author=Durham, Richard| date=2011-08-04 }}</ref> and took part in the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] in his motorboat 'Barbara'.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s2/eastenders/news/a386310/steve-mcfadden-reunites-with-barbara-windsor-during-jubilee-flotilla.html | title=Steve McFadden reunites with Barbara Windsor during Jubilee flotilla | publisher=Digital Spy | date=9 June 2012 | accessdate=1 January 2013 | author=Martinovic, Paul}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he successfully [[sued]] the [[Metropolitan Police]] and ''[[News of the World]]'' after a police officer sold details about him to the newspaper. He sued ''News of the World'' after one of their journalists admitted [[News International phone hacking scandal|trying to intercept his voicemail messages]]. McFadden stated \"I am particularly concerned that a police officer sold my privacy to a tabloid newspaper for profit. I consider the payment of damages and public apology will go some way to ensuring respect for my and others' privacy in future. I am glad to have been vindicated and to be able to put this matter behind me.\"<ref name=\"O'Carroll\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/sep/16/eastenders-steve-mcfadden-settles-damages-news-of-the-world-police-hacking|title=EastEnders star Steve McFadden settles News of the World damages claim |last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=16 September 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Television and film\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes   \n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Buster (film)|Buster]]'' || Gang Member (uncredited) || Film\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' || Mickey || TV series (Episode: \"It's a Sorry Lorry Morrie\")\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Screen Two]]'' || Billy || TV series (Episode: \"The Firm\")\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]'' || Gun Dealer 2 || TV series (Episode: \"Bad Company\")\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Saracen (TV series)|Saracen]]'' || Nash || TV series (Episode: \"Crossfire\")\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]'' || Jones || TV series (Episode: \"Roots of Evil\")\n|-\n| 1990\u20132003<br>2005\u2013present<br /> || ''[[EastEnders]]'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || Soap opera\n|-\n| 1993 || ''[[Dimensions in Time]]'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || ''[[Children in Need]]'' charity special\n|-\n| 1998 || ''EastEnders: The Mitchells - Naked Truths'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || Spin-off video\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Kevin & Perry Go Large]]'' || Bouncer 2 || Film\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Murder in Mind (TV series)|Murder in Mind]]'' || Joe Waterman || TV series (Episode: \"Flame\")\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Comic Relief 2003: The Big Hair Do'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || TV movie\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Provoked: A True Story|Provoked]]'' || DS Ron Meyers || Film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''EastEnders: Last Tango in Walford'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || Spin-off video\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0568711}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFadden, Steve}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of North London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People from Maida Vale]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Steve McFadden\n| image              = Steve McFadden.jpg\n| caption            = McFadden at the 2011 [[The British Soap Awards|British Soap Awards]]\n| birth_name         = Steve Robert Reid\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1959|3|20|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve McFadden|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/celebrities/steve-mcfadden/#~oHzc5qVHJ183Ox|publisher=DigitalSpy|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Maida Vale]], [[London]], England\n| occupation         = [[Actor]]\n| years active       = 1988\u2013present\n| known_for          = ''[[The Bill]]'' (1989)'' <br> [[EastEnders]]'' (1990\u20132003, 2005\u2013)\n| children           = 5\n}}\n'''Steve Robert McFadden''' (n\u00e9 '''Reid''', born 20 March 1959) is an English actor. He is known for his role as [[Phil Mitchell]] in the [[BBC One|BBC]] soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]'', which he has played since 1990. He was also the presenter of fighting series ''[[Britain's Hardest]]''.\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from RADA in 1987,<ref>{{cite web|title=Eastenders actor Steve McFadden hopes to show a 'softer' side of Phil Mitchell|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/entertainment/eastenders_actor_steve_mcfadden_hopes_to_show_a_softer_side_of_phil_mitchell_1_3085685|publisher=Ham&High News|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref> he made his acting debut playing a small role in the 1988 television film ''[[The Firm (1988 film)|The Firm]]''. That same year, he had an uncredited brief appearance in the film ''[[Buster (film)|Buster]]'' as a gang member. This was followed by appearances in the television series ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' and ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]''.\n\nMcFadden then rose to fame for portraying the role of [[Phil Mitchell]] in the [[BBC One|BBC]] soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]''. He joined ''EastEnders'' at the beginning of 1990, at the same time as [[Ross Kemp]], who played Phil's younger brother [[Grant Mitchell (EastEnders)|Grant Mitchell]]. During that time, his character was involved in numerous storylines, such as [[Sharongate]] (where it was revealed that he had an affair with his brother's wife [[Sharon Watts|Sharon]]) in 1994, and the [[Who Shot Phil?]] storyline in March 2001; where his character was shot and wounded by a mystery attacker. The identity of the attacker was revealed weeks later as Phil's girlfriend [[Lisa Fowler|Lisa]], played by [[Lucy Benjamin]].\n\nMcFadden then made an appearance in the film ''[[Kevin & Perry Go Large]]'' in 2000,<ref name=\"Kevin and Perry\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4403694.stm | title=Profiles: EastEnders Kemp and McFadden | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=3 November 2005 | accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> and starred in an episode of the BBC anthology series ''[[Murder in Mind (TV series)|Murder in Mind]]'' in 2001. He left ''EastEnders'' in late 2003 for a one-year break to concentrate on [[pantomimes]]. His character was written out of the series after being framed for an armed robbery by [[Den Watts]] (played by [[Leslie Grantham]]), and going on the run after breaking out of prison. During his break from ''EastEnders'', he presented the reality fighting series ''Britain's Hardest'' which was an underground competition broadcast on [[Sky One]]. He returned to ''EastEnders'' for two episodes in April 2005. In the story, Phil returned to Walford in need of financial help, only to be arrested and returned to prison. In October 2005, he returned on a permanent basis, after his character was cleared of armed robbery.\n\nIn 2007, he appeared in the film ''[[Provoked (film)|Provoked]]''. He has also appeared as Captain Hook in a pantomime production of ''[[Peter Pan (1954 musical)|Peter Pan]]'' from 2010 to 2011 at [[The Swan (theatre)|The Swan]]. From 2012 to 2013, he appeared in ''Aladdin'', playing Abanazar, at the [[Orchard Theatre, Dartford|Orchard Theatre]].\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"20\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"300\"| Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"300\"| Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" width=\"10\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2001 || [[National Television Awards]] || Most Popular Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n|[[British Soap Awards]] || Villain of the Year || {{Won}} \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Inside Soap Awards]] || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Best Bad Boy || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Most Dramatic Storyline ([[Who Shot Phil?]]) || {{Won}}\n|- \n| rowspan=\"3\"|2002 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|British Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Villain of the Year || {{Nom}} \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2003 \n| Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Villain of the Year || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Inside Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|2006\n|rowspan=\"3\"| British Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Villain of the Year || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Spectacular Scene of the Year (skip crashes onto Phil Mitchell's car) || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Inside Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Family ([[Mitchell family]]) || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2007 || [[TV Choice|TVChoice Awards]] || Best Soap Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| [[TV Now Awards]] || Male Soap Star || {{Won}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2008 || British Soap Awards || Spectacular Scene of the Year (Phil Mitchell's car rolling into a lake) || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| [[Digital Spy Soap Awards]] || Best Single Episode (Phil Mitchell and [[Stella Crawford]]'s wedding) || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2009 || British Soap Awards || Best Actor || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2010 \n| rowspan=\"2\"|TV Now Awards || Favourite Male Soap Star || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| Favourite Soap Family (Mitchell family) || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2012 || [[All About Soap|All About Soap Awards]] || Best Mystery (Who's Stalking Phil Mitchell?) || {{Nom}} \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2016 \n| British Soap Awards || Outstanding Achievement Award || {{Won}}\n|-\n| British Soap Awards || Best Male Dramatic Performance || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Inside Soap Awards || Best Soap Actor || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2017\n| British Soap Awards || Best Male Dramatic Performance || {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcFadden has five children. His son Matt McFadden's mother is Sue Marshall, and Angela Bostock is the mother of his daughters Teona and Mollie Jane. Rachel Sidwell gave birth to his daughter Amelie Tinkerbell on 29 June 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/a162792/enders-star-mcfadden-welcomes-baby-girl.html|title='Enders star McFadden welcomes baby girl|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|first=Lara|last=Martin|date=30 June 2009|accessdate=7 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.stv.tv/tv/111723-steve-mcfadden-happier-than-ever/|title=Steve McFadden 'happier than ever'|publisher=MyParkMag|date=26 July 2009|accessdate=29 July 2009}}{{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref> At the time she was his partner, but the couple split two months later.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/200909152023/steve-mcfadden/dr-rachel-sidwell/split|title=Mum of 'EastEnders' actor Steve's new baby calls time on their relationship|date=15 September 2009|accessdate=20 April 2020|work=[[Hello Magazine]]}}</ref> A fifth child, a daughter named Frankie, was born to his girlfriend Karen Cairns in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-steve-mcfadden-dad-fifth-8117039|title=EastEnders' Steve McFadden is 'dad for fifth time with fourth woman, as he welcomes baby daughter' |last=Corner|first=Natalie|date=5 June 2016|work=[[The Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is an active sailor,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yachtingmonthly.com/news/529359/tv-star-s-loathing-for-gin-palaces | title=TV star's loathing for gin palaces | publisher=Yachting Monthly | accessdate=1 January 2013 | author=Durham, Richard| date=2011-08-04 }}</ref> and took part in the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] in his motorboat 'Barbara'.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s2/eastenders/news/a386310/steve-mcfadden-reunites-with-barbara-windsor-during-jubilee-flotilla.html | title=Steve McFadden reunites with Barbara Windsor during Jubilee flotilla | publisher=Digital Spy | date=9 June 2012 | accessdate=1 January 2013 | author=Martinovic, Paul}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he successfully [[sued]] the [[Metropolitan Police]] and ''[[News of the World]]'' after a police officer sold details about him to the newspaper. He sued ''News of the World'' after one of their journalists admitted [[News International phone hacking scandal|trying to intercept his voicemail messages]]. McFadden stated \"I am particularly concerned that a police officer sold my privacy to a tabloid newspaper for profit. I consider the payment of damages and public apology will go some way to ensuring respect for my and others' privacy in future. I am glad to have been vindicated and to be able to put this matter behind me.\"<ref name=\"O'Carroll\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/sep/16/eastenders-steve-mcfadden-settles-damages-news-of-the-world-police-hacking|title=EastEnders star Steve McFadden settles News of the World damages claim |last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=16 September 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Television and film\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes   \n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Buster (film)|Buster]]'' || Gang Member (uncredited) || Film\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' || Mickey || TV series (Episode: \"It's a Sorry Lorry Morrie\")\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Screen Two]]'' || Billy || TV series (Episode: \"The Firm\")\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]'' || Gun Dealer 2 || TV series (Episode: \"Bad Company\")\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Saracen (TV series)|Saracen]]'' || Nash || TV series (Episode: \"Crossfire\")\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]'' || Jones || TV series (Episode: \"Roots of Evil\")\n|-\n| 1990\u20132003<br>2005\u2013present<br /> || ''[[EastEnders]]'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || Soap opera\n|-\n| 1993 || ''[[Dimensions in Time]]'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || ''[[Children in Need]]'' charity special\n|-\n| 1998 || ''EastEnders: The Mitchells - Naked Truths'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || Spin-off video\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Kevin & Perry Go Large]]'' || Bouncer 2 || Film\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Murder in Mind (TV series)|Murder in Mind]]'' || Joe Waterman || TV series (Episode: \"Flame\")\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Comic Relief 2003: The Big Hair Do'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || TV movie\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Provoked: A True Story|Provoked]]'' || DS Ron Meyers || Film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''EastEnders: Last Tango in Walford'' || [[Phil Mitchell]] || Spin-off video\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0568711}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFadden, Steve}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of North London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People from Maida Vale]]\n", "name_user": "101.98.113.134", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_McFadden"}
{"title_page": "Miss Anthropocene", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Miss Anthropocene\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]]\n| cover        = Grimes - Miss Anthropocene.png\n| alt          = \n| released     = February 21, 2020\n| recorded     = 2017<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=grimezsz|number=1003875361224945666|title=well i said i'd post some snippets of new music earlier so this prob sounds terrible thru my phone recording but it's the cheesy love song i was talking about that i don't like but everyone else likes, made the instrumental w my new mellotron!pic.twitter.com/KDZLIY8OcF|date=June 4, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\u20132019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/post/sa.6a853580-cf7c-11e9-9733-2c4dc49169a5|title=Listen to \"Zane Lowe and Grimes\" posted by Zane Lowe on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| genre        = <!-- Do not add unsourced genres -->\n* [[Industrial music|Industrial]]<ref name=\"Best pop songs\">{{cite web |last1=D'Souza |first1=Shaad |title=The 20 best pop songs right now |url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/03/02/20-best-pop-songs-february-2020-100-gecs-lady-gaga-justin-bieber-list |website=[[The Fader|The FADER]] |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"Best pop songs\"/>\n* [[electropop]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Torres |first1=Eric |title=Grimes Dissects the Visual World of ''Miss Anthropocene'' |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/interview/grimes-miss-anthropocene-interview/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| length       = 44:40\n| label        = [[4AD]]\n| producer     =\n* [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]]\n* [[Dan Carey (record producer)|Dan Carey]]\n* i_o\n* [[Hana (American musician)|Hana]]\n* Chris Greatti\n| prev_title   = [[Art Angels]]\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Extra album cover\n| header       = Deluxe edition cover\n| type         = studio\n| cover        = Miss Anthropocene deluxe cover.png\n| caption      = \n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Miss Anthropocene\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Violence (song)|Violence]]\n | single1date = September 5, 2019\n | single2     = So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\n | single2date = November 15, 2019\n | single3     = [[My Name Is Dark]]\n | single3date = November 29, 2019\n | single4     = 4\u00c6M\n | single4date = December 13, 2019\n | single5     = [[Delete Forever]]\n | single5date = February 12, 2020\n<!-- Don't add any singles here until they're actually released. Grimes saying she plans to release something doesn't mean it will happen. -->\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Miss Anthropocene''''' is the fifth studio album by Canadian musician [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], released on February 21, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-grimes-new-song-so-heavy-i-fell-through-the-earth/|title=Grimes Details New Album Miss Anthropocene, Shares New Song: Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]|last1=Bloom|first1=Madison|last2=Monroe|first2=Jazz|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> It was officially announced on March 19, 2019.<ref name=\"Pitchfork announcement\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/grimes-announces-new-album-miss-anthropocene/|title=Grimes Announces New Album ''Miss_Anthropocene''|website=Pitchfork|last1=Bloom|first1=Madison|last2=Blais-Billie|first2=Braudie|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/43752/1/grimes-announces-her-new-album-miss-anthropocene|title=Grimes announces her new album Miss_Anthropocene|website=[[Dazed]]|last=Cafolla|first=Anna|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The album's name is a pun on the feminine title \"Miss\", and the words \"[[misanthrope]]\" and \"[[Anthropocene]]\",<ref>{{cite tweet|user=Grimezsz|number=1108202117813043200|title=New Album Announcement! pic.twitter.com/bAegemOQm5|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Grimezsz/status/1108202117813043200/photo/1|title=Twitter|via=[[Twitter]]|archiveurl=http://archive.is/xjfa9|archivedate=November 12, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> a [[neologism]] popularised in the year 2000 by [[Paul J. Crutzen]] that was proposed to denote the current geological age the Earth is in.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/aug/29/declare-anthropocene-epoch-experts-urge-geological-congress-human-impact-earth|title=The Anthropocene epoch: scientists declare dawn of human-influenced age|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Carrington|first=Damian|date=August 29, 2016|accessdate=November 18, 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Anthropocene|title=Definition of ANTHROPOCENE|website=merriam-webster.com|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The album is a loose [[concept album]] about an \"[[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] goddess of [[climate change]]\" inspired by [[Roman mythology]]<ref name=\"NME Richards\" /> and [[villainy]].<ref name=\"Crack\" /> ''Miss Anthropocene'' is Grimes' final album on record label [[4AD]], to which she has been signed since 2012.<ref name=\"NME Skinner\" /> The album is darker in style than Grimes' 2015 album ''[[Art Angels]]'', containing inspiration from the sounds of [[nu metal]] and [[ethereal wave]].\n\n==Background and release==\nOn December 16, 2017, Grimes responded to fan on [[Twitter]] that she had \"played [her] label new music\", indicating that something would be released soon.<ref name=\"NME Richards\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/grimes-new-album-miss_anthropocene-release-date-tracklist-everything-know-far-2531642|title=Grimes' new album 'Miss_Anthropocene': release date, tracklist and everything we know so far|work=[[NME]]|last=Richards|first=Will|date=August 13, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Among marked disagreements with her record label [[4AD]],<ref name=\"NME Skinner\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/grimes-apologises-calling-4ad-shit-label-2249609|title=Grimes apologises for calling 4AD a \"shit label\"|work=NME|last=Skinner|first=Tom|date=February 27, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/feb/27/madonna-grimes-female-artists-labels|title=Madonna and Grimes lay bare cost of creative freedom for female artists|work=The Guardian|last=Snapes|first=Laura|date=February 27, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Grimes later announced that she had hoped to release a new album in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/grimes-says-new-album-out-this-year/|title=Grimes Says New Album Out This Year|website=Pitchfork|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=February 1, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> On February 24, 2018, Grimes revealed that she was in the process of recording two albums<ref name=\"NME Skinner\"/> to follow up her 2015 album ''[[Art Angels]]''. In May 2018, some working titles were shared via her [[Instagram]] story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/grimes-shares-working-tracklist-for-new-album/|title=Grimes Shares \"Working\" Tracklist for New Album|website=Pitchfork|last=Kim|first=Michelle|date=May 13, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> In June 2018, Grimes was featured in [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s ''Behind the Mac'' advertisement campaign in which a snippet of a song titled \"That's What the Drugs Are For\" was featured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2001839/grimes-stars-in-apple-commercial-featuring-her-new-song-thats-what-the-drugs-are-for/video/|title=Grimes Stars In Apple Commercial Featuring Her New Song \"That\u2019s What The Drugs Are For\"|website=[[Stereogum]]|last=DeVille|first=Chris|date=June 15, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe album's title was announced on March 19, 2019. Grimes explained that the album would be a concept album about an \"anthropomorphic goddess of climate change\" in which \"each song will be a different embodiment of human extinction\".<ref name=\"Pitchfork announcement\"/> Grimes explained that she \"love[s] godly personifications of abstract/horrific concepts\", pointing to the Roman god of war [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]] as an inspiration; and that by making a personification of climate change she hoped that it would \"maybe ... be a bit easier to look at\" and not be \"just abstract doom\".<ref name=\"NME Richards\"/> In an interview with ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', Grimes further explained that \"people don't care about it [climate change], because we're being guilted.\" Grimes stated that she wanted \"to make climate change fun\" and \"make a reason to look at it\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/grimes-talks-new-album-elon-musk-more-in-rare-interview/|title=Grimes Talks New Album, Elon Musk, More in Rare Interview|website=Pitchfork|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Miss Anthropocene''{{'}}s darker themes were also inspired by Grimes' reputation during the album's creation. Grimes elaborated in her interview with ''[[Crack Magazine]]'' that she had been made out to be a villain in the media due to large publications misrepresenting things she had said and the media's criticism of her relationship with [[Elon Musk]], claiming that publications ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', and ''[[The Guardian]]'' had spread falsehoods about her, deriding that \"we really do live in a [[post-truth]] society\". Grimes stated that if she was going to be \"stuck being a villain\" then she wanted \"to pursue villainy artistically\", saying that it is \"a really fun idea\" to her, naming characters [[The Joker]] and [[Thanos]] as inspirations.<ref name=\"Crack\">{{Cite web|url=https://crackmagazine.net/article/long-reads/grimes-is-ready-to-play-the-villain/|title=Cover Story: Grimes is ready to play the villain|work=[[Crack Magazine]]|last=Perry|first=Kevin EG|date=April 16, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Zane Lowe]] on [[Apple Music]]'s ''[[Beats 1]]'' radio station, Grimes revealed that ''Miss Anthropocene'' had actually been finished for some time and she was already working on her next album, which would be a \"techno-pop album\" where she \"works with [her] favourite producers\". Grimes mentioned that despite it being her favourite album, she had already \"moved on\" from the dark themes of ''Miss Anthropocene'', which were caused by \"a fair number of things that were going on at the time [of its creation].\" She also stated that the song \"[[Violence (song)|Violence]]\" was intended for the unnamed sixth album but was included on ''Miss Anthropocene'' because the track \"feels good\". In this interview Grimes also stated that one of the reasons for the album's delayed release was the death of her former manager Lauren Valencia from cancer in July 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/lauren-valencia-manager-my-chemical-romance-grimes-1203265903/|title=Lauren Valencia, Manager of My Chemical Romance and Grimes, Dies|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=''Variety'' staff|date=July 12, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/post/sa.6a853580-cf7c-11e9-9733-2c4dc49169a5|title=Listen to \"Zane Lowe and Grimes\" posted by Zane Lowe on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> an event which impacted Grimes greatly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/09/05/grimes-charli-xcx-collaboration-interview-miss-anthropocene-violence|title=Grimes says she's working with Charli XCX on a \"psychotic techno song\"|website=[[The Fader]]|last=Maicki|first=Salvatore|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn unfinished version of the album leaked online in September 2019, with a finalized version leaking in November 2019.<ref name=\"ElijahAura\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elijahaura.com/albumreview/grimesmissanthropocene|title='Miss Anthropocene' - Grimes [REVIEW] \u2014 AURA Review|website=Aura|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> On October 15, 2019, Grimes revealed via a reply to a fan on Instagram that physical copies of ''Miss Anthropocene'' were in the process of being pressed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8533161/grimes-new-album-2019-way-done|title=Grimes Says Fifth Studio Album Is 'Way Done'|website=Billboard|last=Payne|first=Chris|date=October 16, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> ''Miss Anthropocene'' was officially released on February 21, 2020.\n\n==Promotion==\n\n===Singles===\nOriginally billed to be the first single from the album,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/11/watch-grimes-we-appreciate-power-video.html|title=Grimes Shares Video for \"We Appreciate Power,\" Her First Proper Solo Single Since 2015|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Kamp|first=Justin|date=November 29, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/grimes-returns-new-track-appreciate-power-inspired-ai-north-korea-2414308|title=Grimes returns with new track 'We Appreciate Power', inspired by AI and North Korea|work=NME|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=November 29, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> \"[[We Appreciate Power]]\", featuring American singer [[Hana (American musician)|Hana]], was released on November 29, 2018. The track was met with praise from music reviewers who acclaimed the song's [[electronic rock]] sound and lyrics revolving around themes of [[transhumanism]] and [[artificial intelligence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/grimes-we-appreciate-power-track-review-2414369|title=Grimes has turned into an industrial-goth AI bot and I, for one, welcome our new robot overlord|work=NME|last=Stubbs|first=Dan|date=November 29, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8487138/grimes-we-appreciate-power-hana|title=Grimes Storms Back With Dark AI-Inspired 'We Appreciate Power' Featuring Hana: Listen|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=November 29, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> It was also noted that Grimes had been in a relationship with technology entrepreneur Elon Musk since 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/07/26/photo-elon-musk-girlfriend-confusing-lot-people-7765125/|title=This photo of Elon Musk and his girlfriend is confusing a lot of people|website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|last=Hamill|first=Jasper|date=July 26, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> leading to speculation that the song was inspired by him and his work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theoutline.com/post/6717/grimes-we-appreciate-power-review-elon-musk|title=From Grimes to Elon, with love|website=[[The Outline (website)|The Outline]]|last=Gordon|first=Jeremy|date=November 29, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gizmodo.com.au/2018/05/i-had-no-idea-who-grimes-is-but-after-20-minutes-of-misinformed-research-reports-shes-dating-elon-musk-make-sense/|title=I Had No Idea Who Grimes Is, But After 20 Minutes Of Misinformed Research, Reports She's Dating Elon Musk Make Sense|website=[[Gizmodo Australia]]|last=McKay|first=Tom|date=May 8, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> On November 15, 2019, it was revealed the track would only be included on the digital deluxe edition and Japanese CD release of the album.\n\nIn an Instagram post published on August 13, 2019, Grimes announced the first official single from ''Miss Anthropocene'' would be released on September 13, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/08/grimes-miss-anthropocene-album-tease/|title=Grimes Teases First Single From New Album 'Miss_Anthropocene': Watch|website=Spin|last=Burks|first=Tosten|date=August 13, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> This post was deleted shortly afterwards. On September 3, 2019, Grimes deleted all of her Instagram posts then announced in a new post that a song would be released on September 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/grimes-a-new-way-to-die-new-single-2544437|title=Grimes confirms new single 'A New Day To Die' will arrive this week|work=NME|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B18SKOQlgMn/|title=Grimes on Instagram: \"A new way to die! 2 days.\"|via=Instagram|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The song, originally speculated to be titled \"A New Way to Die\" due to the caption of her Instagram post, was clarified later to actually be called \"Violence\". The track features American DJ i_o.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/09/grimes-i_o-violence-video-watch/|title=Grimes Releases Video for New Song \"Violence\": Watch|website=Spin|last=Cook-Wilson|first=Winston|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Dazed]]'' praised the track's \"thumping kickdrum and synth arp bassline\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/45873/1/grimes-io-violence-watch-music-video|title=Grimes returns with a new single, 'Violence'|website=Dazed|last=Bulut|first=Selim|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> During the music video's premiere on YouTube, Grimes announced that she would be releasing two songs, titled \"So Heavy I Fell Through The Earth\" and \"4\u00c6M\", as the album's next two singles although no release dates were given.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/grimes-releases-new-song-video-violence/|title=Grimes Releases New Song & Video 'Violence'|website=[[Music Feeds]]|last=Langford|first=Sebastian|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/grimes-violence-music-video-miss-anthropocene-2545058|title=Watch Grimes turn into an ethereal goddess for new 'Violence' music video|work=NME|last=Ramli|first=Sofiana|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe second official single from ''Miss Anthropocene'', \"So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\", was announced via Instagram on November 11, 2019, and released on November 15, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4vd_gQlP5U/|title=Grimes on Instagram: \"Hooo boy finally just got release dates for things from label this AM ..... SO HEAVY I FELL THROUGH THE EARTH Fri\"|via=Instagram|date=November 12, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/grimes-to-release-new-song-so-heavy-this-week-2566939|title=Grimes to release new song 'So Heavy' this week|work=NME|last=Richards|first=Will|date=November 11, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The cover art and track listing for ''Miss Anthropocene'' were also unveiled on November 15. The track received positive reviews from critics who commented on the track's slower and darker sound compared to the previous single \"Violence\", with ''[[NME]]'' stating that it felt like a \"slow-motion fall through the cosmos\", noting the track's \"thick layers of bass\" and \"Grimes' dangling voice\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/track/grimes-so-heavy-i-fell-through-the-earth-track-review|title=Grimes' 'So Heavy I Fell Through The Earth' is an otherworldly meander through the galaxy|work=NME|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> ''Pitchfork'' labelled the track a \"six-minute downtempo odyssey\" with \"forceful theatrics\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/grimes-so-heavy-i-fell-through-the-earth/|title=Listen to \"So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\" by Grimes|website=Pitchfork|last=Torres|first=Eric|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe third single from the album, \"[[My Name Is Dark]]\" \u2014 originally titled \"That's What The Drugs Are For\"<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=Grimezsz|number=1200328807950893057|title=Yes, I tried i re title it back to that yesterday but it was too late hahaha so now it\u2019s dark 4evr|date=November 29, 2020|accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref> \u2014 was released on November 29, 2019. The track's nu-metal sound was praised by many publications, with ''[[Stereogum]]'' calling it a \"dark and gritty electro-rocker\" with a \"menacing guitar riff\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2066424/grimes-my-name-is-dark/music/|title=Grimes - \"My Name Is Dark\"|date=2019-11-29|website=Stereogum|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2019, Grimes premiered the fourth single from ''Miss Anthropocene'', \"4\u00c6M\", at [[The Game Awards 2019]] during the segment dedicated to the soundtrack of the upcoming video game ''[[Cyberpunk 2077]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/grimes-debuts-4m-at-game-awards-watch.html|title=Grimes Is One Step Closer to Being a Cyborg in Her Game Awards Performance|last=Squires|first=Bethy|date=2019-12-13|website=Vulture|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Game Awards 2019 (Full Event)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2T16EmGccMM|via=[[YouTube]]|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> Grimes also announced that she is the voice actor for a character in the game named Lizzy Wizzy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2067774/grimes-4aem-game-awards-lizzy-wizzy-cyberpunk-2077/video/|title=Grimes Debuts \"4\u00c6M,\" Will Portray Pop Star Lizzy Wizzy In Cyberpunk 2077|date=2019-12-12|website=Stereogum|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> \"4\u00c6M\" samples the song \"Deewani Mastani\" from the [[Bollywood]] film [[Bajirao Mastani]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theedgesusu.co.uk/records/singles/2019/12/19/review-grimes-4aem/|title=Review \u2013 Grimes: \u20184\u00c6M\u2019|date=2019-12-19|website=The Edge|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> and was described by Grimes as being a \"cyberpunk interpretation\" of the film. ''NME'' named the track \"suitably futuristic\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/grimes-debuts-new-track-4aem-from-cyberpunk-2077-soundtrack-2587627|title=Grimes debuts new track '4\u00c6M' from 'Cyberpunk 2077' soundtrack|work=NME|date=December 13, 2019|accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref> while other reviewers praised the song's [[drum and bass]] beat and ethereal vocals, noting similarities to songs from Grimes' 2010 album ''[[Halfaxa]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/listen-grimes-4%C3%A6m|title=Listen: Grimes - '4\u00c6M'|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elijahaura.com/singlereview/grimes4am|title='4 \u00c6M' - Grimes [REVIEW]|website=AURA|access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth single from the album, \"Delete Forever\", was released on February 12, 2020. The song was inspired by Grimes losing six of her friends to heroin overdoses and the numbness Grimes felt following their deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/grimes-delete-forever-lyrical-meaning-drug-opioid-abuse-2612108|title=Grimes reveals lyrical meaning of 'Delete Forever' discusses her friends' opiod-related deaths|website=NME|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> It was written on the same night that [[emo rap]] artist [[Lil Peep]] accidentally died after overdosing on a fake [[Xanax]] pill that was laced with [[fentanyl]].<ref name=\"FactDelete\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2020/02/12/grimes-delete-forever-video/|title=Grimes sits atop a crumbled empire in new 'Delete Forever' video|website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=February 12, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-peep-cause-of-death-revealed-202399/|title=Lil Peep Cause of Death Revealed|website=Rolling Stone|last=Grow|first=Kory|date=December 8, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> In an interview with [[Genius (website)|Genius]], Grimes explained that she wanted the song to have a sound that is \"opposite\" to the music she normal makes, with a \"raw punk\" feel and a \"super clean vocal\" with no digital processing and effects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/grimes-breaks-down-the-meaning-of-delete-forever|title=Grimes Breaks Down The Meaning Of \"Delete Forever\"|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Videos===\nSeveral lyric videos were released for various songs from ''Miss Anthropocene''. A lyric video for \"We Appreciate Power\" was released on November 28, 2019. It features both Grimes and Hana and was directed by the former alongside her brother Mac Boucher.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alston|first=Trey|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-grimes-new-song-we-appreciate-power|title=Listen to Grimes' New Song \"We Appreciate Power\"|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=November 29, 2018|accessdate=November 29, 2018}}</ref> Another lyric video for the album's third single \"My Name Is Dark\" followed on December 3, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/12/03/grimes-shares-my-name-is-dark-lyric-video-talks-with-lana-del-rey-for-interview|title=Grimes shares \"My Name Is Dark\" lyric video, talks with Lana Del Rey for Interview|website=The Fader|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> Grimes described it as \"just a cute vibe\".<ref name=\"ElijahAura\"/> On February 27, 2020, Grimes released two lyric videos for the track \"Idoru\". Dubbed \"Slightly Longer Version\" and \"Slightly Shorter Version\", they correspond to the \"Art Mix\" and \"Algorithm Mix\" versions of the song, respectively. Grimes released the videos after noticing that the track was a fan favorite.<ref>{{cite web|last=Legaspi|first=Althea|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/grimes-idoru-video-watch-959466/|title=Grimes Plays the Game of Love in New 'Idoru' Video|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo music videos were released. The video for the lead single \"Violence\" was released on September 5, 2019 and was directed by Grimes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-grimes-video-for-new-song-violence/|title=Watch Grimes' Video for New Song \"Violence\"|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> Its acclaimed choreography, described by ''Variety'' as \"mock pistol-firing and swordplay\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/grimes-drops-new-single-and-video-violence-1203324574/|title=Grimes Drops New Single and Video, 'Violence'|work=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> is inspired by [[TikTok]] user Cindy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sanchez|first=Chelsey|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a31022820/grimes-violence-music-video-playback/|title=Grimes's Dance for the \"Violence\" Music Video Was Inspired by This TikTok|work=[[Harper's Bazaar]]|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Another video was released for the fifth single \"Delete Forever\" on February 12, 2020. It was directed by Grimes, Mac Boucher, and Neil Hansen, and depicts \"a tyrant's lament as her empire crumbles\".<ref name=\"FactDelete\"/>\n\nA \"visualizer\" for the album's second single \"So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\" was uploaded on November 15, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ward|first=Billy|url=https://www.dummymag.com/new-music/grimes-so-heavy-i-fell-through-the-earth/|title=Grimes drops celestial cut 'So Heavy I Fell Through The Earth'|work=Dummy Magazine|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, Grimes uploaded a [[green screen]] video for the track \"You'll Miss Me When I'm Not Around\" to her YouTube channel as well as an archive featuring the raw audio and video files to [[WeTransfer]] and invited her fans to remix the song and the video using the hashtag #GrimesArtKit. The footage was originally shot so that her artistic team could create visuals for the album,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/2/21205769/grimes-music-stems-video-files-wetransfer-youll-miss-me-when-im-not-around-remix-coronavirus|title=Grimes posted the music stems and video files for her single so anyone can remix it|first=Dani|last=Deahl|website=[[The Verge]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> but she cited the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] as the reason she elected to involve her fans, in case they are \"bored and wanna learn new things\" while on lockdown.<ref name=\"NME-artkit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/grimes-encourages-fans-to-finish-her-music-video-for-youll-miss-me-when-im-not-around-2639476|title=Grimes encourages fans to finish her music video for 'You'll Miss Me When I'm Not Around'|first=Josh|last=Martin|website=[[NME]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> ''Billboard'' speculated that this may also relate to Grimes' roots in the DIY scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9348765/grimes-youll-miss-me-when-im-not-around-video|title=Grimes Asks Fans to Collaborate on 'You'll Miss Me When I'm Not Around' Video|first=Heran|last=Mamo|website=[[Billboard (magazine) |Billboard]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nMiss Anthropocene has debuted at No. 1 on Billboard's Top Dance/Electronic Albums chart, with 19,000 equivalent album units, according to Nielsen Music/MRC Data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9328800/grimes-first-no-1-top-dance-electronic-albums-chart-miss-anthropocene|title=Grimes Earns First No. 1 on Top Dance/Electronic Albums Chart With 'Miss Anthropocene'|publisher=Billboard|date=5 March 2020|first=Gordon|last=Murray|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/10268/Grimes-Miss-Anthropocene.aspx|title=Miss Anthropocene by Grimes reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 79/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/miss-anthropocene/grimes|title=Miss Anthropocene by Grimes|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic rev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/miss-anthropocene-mw0003337691|title=Miss Anthropocene \u2013 Grimes|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Phares|first=Heather|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = B+<ref name=\"Consequence of Sound rev\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/album-review-grimes-miss-anthrop0cene/|title=Grimes Finds a Creative Spark on the Magnificent Miss_Anthrop0cene|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Sharples|first=Grant|date=February 16, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Daily Telegraph rev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/grimes-miss-anthropocene-review-meet-evil-goddess-eco-pop//|title=Grimes, Miss Anthropocene, review: meet the evil goddess of eco-pop|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=McCormick|first=Neil|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Guardian rev\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/feb/20/grimes-miss-anthropocene-review-4ad|title=Grimes: Miss Anthropocene review \u2013 a toxicity report on modern celebrity|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent rev\">{{cite web|last=Gill|first=Andy|date=February 21, 2020|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/grimes-miss-anthropocene-review-album-lyrics-tracklist-elon-musk-lil-peep-a9344901.html/|title=Grimes, Miss Anthropocene \u2013 album review|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME rev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/grimes-miss-anthropocene-review-2612446|title=Grimes \u2013 'Miss Anthropocene'|work=[[NME]]|last=Nicolson|first=Barry|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Magazine]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Now rev\">{{cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/grimes-miss-anthropocene/|title=Review: Miss Anthropocene is Grimes's best album|work=[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]]|last=Edwards|first=Samantha|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| rev8score = 5.6/10<ref name=\"Paste rev\">{{cite web|last1=Freedman|first1=Max|title=Grimes\u2019 Miss_Anthropocene Veers on Incoherent|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2020/02/grimes-miss-anthropocene-review.html|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=February 21, 2020|date=February 21, 2020|}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9score = 8.2/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork rev\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/grimes-miss-anthropocene|title=Grimes: Miss Anthropocene Album Review|website=Pitchfork|last=Hopper|first=Jessica|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone rev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/grimes-miss-anthropocene-review-950388/|title=Miss Anthropocene|work=Rolling Stone|last=Dolan|first=Jon|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Miss Anthropocene'' received positive reviews from music critics upon its release. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]], which assigns media a [[Standard score|normalized]] score out of 100 based on reviews from mainstream publications, the album has a score of 79 which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\" based on 27 critic reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Writing for ''[[The Independent]]'', Adam White acclaimed the dark themes and wide range of sounds on the album, saying that it \"operates much like a greatest hits record\". He directed praise to the album's slower songs, particularly \"So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\" and \"You'll Miss Me When I'm Not Around\", comparing the latter to songs by [['Til Tuesday]] and [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]].<ref name=\"The Independent rev\"/> [[Alexis Petridis]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised the \"prosaic, realistic and affecting\" lyrics throughout the album while questioning its concept and criticizing some of its \"musical experiments\" such as the chorus of \"4\u00c6M\" and the \"smeared\" vocals of \"New Gods\".<ref name=\"The Guardian rev\"/> Rhian Daly of ''[[NME]]'' expressed a similar opinion in regards to the album's concept, calling it \"fragmented ... rather than being a unifying thing to tie every song neatly together\", and praised ''Miss Anthropocene''{{'}}s mix of sounds, pointing to the \"eerie\" \"New Gods\" and \"intergalactic rave-pop\" of \"Violence\" as highlights while acclaiming the album's \"euphoric\" closer \"Idoru\".<ref name=\"NME rev\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Standard edition<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/miss-anthropocene/1487294744|title=Miss Anthropocene by Grimes|website=Apple Music|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| all_writing = [[Claire Boucher]], except where noted\n| title1 = So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\n| note1 = Art Mix\n| length1 = 6:08\n| title2 = Darkseid\n| note2 = with \u6f58PAN; writers: Boucher, Pan Wei-Ju\n| length2 = 3:44\n| title3 = [[Delete Forever]]\n| length3 = 3:57\n| title4 = [[Violence (song)|Violence]]\n| note4 = with i_o; writers: Boucher, Garrett Lockhart\n| length4 = 3:40\n| title5 = 4\u00c6M\n| note5 = writers: Boucher, Ganesh Chandanshive, Siddharth-Garima, Sanjal Bhandari, Nasir Faraaz\n| length5 = 4:30\n| title6 = New Gods\n| note6 = producers: Boucher, [[Dan Carey (record producer)|Dan Carey]]\n| length6 = 3:15\n| title7 = [[My Name Is Dark]]\n| note7 = Art Mix\n| length7 = 5:56\n| title8 = You'll Miss Me When I'm Not Around\n| length8 = 2:41\n| title9 = Before the Fever\n| length9 = 3:37\n| title10 = Idoru\n| note10 = Art Mix\n| length10 = 7:12\n| total_length = 44:40\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Japanese CD edition bonus track<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diskunion.net/indiealt/ct/detail/AWS191115GRIMES|title=MISS ANTHROPOCENE / \u30df\u30b9\u30fb\u30a2\u30f3\u30c8\u30ed\u30dd\u30bb\u30f3/GRIMES/\u30b0\u30e9\u30a4\u30e0\u30b9\uff5cROCK / POPS / INDIE\uff5c\u30c7\u30a3\u30b9\u30af\u30e6\u30cb\u30aa\u30f3\uff65\u30aa\u30f3\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7|website=diskunion.net|language=ja|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| total_length = 50:15\n| title11 = [[We Appreciate Power]]\n| note11 = featuring [[Hana (American musician)|Hana]]; writers: Boucher, Hana Pestle, Chris Greatti\n| length11 = 5:35\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Deluxe digital version bonus tracks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/ca/album/miss-anthropocene-deluxe/1488048682|title=Miss Anthropocene (Deluxe) by Grimes|website=Apple Music|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| total_length = 67:08\n| title12 = So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\n| note12 = Algorithm Mix\n| length12 = 3:52\n| title13 = [[Violence (song)|Violence]]\n| note13 = with i_o) (Club Mix\n| length13 = 4:12\n| title14 = [[My Name Is Dark]]\n| note14 = Algorithm Mix\n| length14 = 4:03\n| title15 = Idoru\n| note15 = Algorithm Mix\n| length15 = 4:46\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* The vinyl version contains the \"algorithm mix\" versions of \"So Heavy I Fell Through the Earth\", \"My Name Is Dark\", and \"Idoru\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://4ad.com/|title=The official website for independent record label 4AD.|website=4AD|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/grimes-miss-anthropocene-so-heavy/|title=Grimes releases cover, tracklist and release date for new album 'Miss Anthropocene'|website=Tone Deaf|last=Di Iorio|first=Michael|date=November 16, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* \"You'll Miss Me When I'm Not Around\" and \"Before the Fever\" are stylized in [[sentence case]].\n* \"Idoru\" is stylized in [[all caps]].\n\n==Personnel==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]] \u2013 vocals, production, engineering\n* i_o \u2013 production {{small|(track 4)}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/09/grimes-i_o-violence-video-watch/|title=Grimes Releases Video for New Song \"Violence\": Watch|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|last=Cook-Wilson|first=Winston|date=September 5, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* Chris Greatti \u2013 production {{small|(track 11)}}<ref name=\"Chris Greatti\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bqx8Z--l9V2/|title=Chris Greatti on Instagram: \"N\u00fc @grimes opus \"We Appreciate Power\" out now! G and I co-produced it, she @hanatruly and I wrote it, @zakkcervini mixed it. Simply by...\"|via=Instagram|date=January 1, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Hana Pestle|Hana]] \u2013 vocals, additional production {{small|(track 11)}}<ref name=\"Chris Greatti\"